[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Benko Gambit"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Hello my name is Dalton Perrine, and I welcome you to this Chessable course!   I'm a FIDE Master with over 19 years of over-the-board tournament experience and over eight years of coaching experience, having taught hundreds of students in 1-on-1 and group settings.   I have previously created a tactics course here on Chessable focused on defensive calculation and blunder prevention titled 'Survive and Thrive: How to Blunder Less and Defend Better'.  I also worked along with GM Yaroslav Zherebukh to do the video presentation for the White opening course 'The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack'.  Now I am happy to bring you my first full opening course, which focuses on the Benko Gambit, an opening that I have played all my life and is near and dear to my heart.} 1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5 {The starting moves for the Benko Gambit. The Benko Gambit (also known as the Volga Gambit in some countries) was first popularized by Hungarian-American Grandmaster Pal Benko in the late 1960s.   Pal Benko also wrote a book about the opening titled 'The Benko Gambit' in 1974 where he left his stamp on the opening and its history. Myself, I have played the Benko Gambit ever since my first coach taught it to me over 15 years ago. I have typically played the ...g6 and ...Bxa6 variations throughout my playing history, but once I discovered the 5...e6 variation about two years ago then, that's been my preferred Benko Gambit variation of choice ever since then.   The Benko Gambit is a very fun and dynamic opening with lots of interesting positions involving material sacrifices, compensation and counterplay. The main idea behind this opening is to sacrifice one of Black's queenside pawns in return for eliminating White's c4-pawn which is defending their central d5-pawn.If White accepts the gambit with4.cxb5then Black will follow up with4...a6, confirming the gambit, and this is done to get strong queenside pressure against White's a2 and b2-pawns once the a- and b-files open up for Black's rooks.White has alternative options on the fourth and fifth moves if they do not want to accept the gambit and capture the pawn on b5 or a6 and these variations will be explored more in their respective chapters.The main Benko Gambit Accepted variation that this course will emphasize continues with4.cxb5a65.bxa6e6!?which will be explained more in the devoted chapter. Finally, alternative sidelines on the second and third moves will be explained in their respective chapters too.  One final note: The large majority of variations throughout the course (including non-Benko Gambit variations) will focus on a quick ...c5 advance in order to attack White's central d5-pawn. Get ready to break apart White's center!} 
