 {There are many ways you can work through this course but the one I recommend is the following:   1. Start by reading the What is Compensation? chapter. Learning how to evaluate positions correctly and how to play around with compensation is an integral part of understanding and playing this repertoire well.   2. Go through the three (#1, #2 and #3) Quickstarter chapters. This will give you a strong starting point for playing the repertoire.   3. Go through the Model Games chapter. You will find it helpful to see strong players play the opening lines in this course and how they were able to navigate the resulting middlegames and endgames (especially if they were down material).   4. Play games! This can be online blitz games, over-the-board games, training games, playing against the computer or whatever you want to do. It is important to practice the lines in the course and build up some experience with them.   5. Work your way through the 18 theoretical chapters. I recommend using the 'Important Lines' feature to begin with. This will shrink your workload quite a bit and make the course more manageable rather than feeling like you need to learn and memorize every single variation. Once you've gone through all the important lines, then you can go through the remaining ones. Or if you played a game that had a variation from the course, then go review that line whether it is 'important' or not.   6. Solve from the Puzzles chapter. I don't recommend going through all the puzzles in one sitting. Rather, it is probably better to do a few per day, maybe as a warm-up before you play your training games or before you study the course for the day.   7. Maybe check out the My Blitz Games chapter at some point. But don't treat these games as model games! You've been warned :-)} 1. --
