[White "What is Compensation?"]
[Black "Definition"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {'Compensation' is a term that you will see many, many times throughout this course. With that in mind, I wanted to include a chapter early in the course here that will give you a good understanding about it.   To begin with, 'compensation' is defined as 'the positional or dynamic advantages one side has in return for material loss'.   Compensation can come in many forms, such as being down material but having the advantage of:   a lead in development; the initiative and attacking chances; your opponent's king being weak and exposed; having the bishop pair; giving your opponent weak pawns; open diagonals for bishops or open files for rooks... etc.  
Typically the amount of compensation you need to have is related to the amount of material you have sacrificed or invested. If you have sacrificed one pawn, then you may not need as much compensation to make up for the pawn deficit.   However, if you have sacrificed a few pawns, a minor piece, a rook or a queen, then you will need higher amounts of compensation or other bigger advantages to make up for the higher amounts of invested material.   Another thing to understand is that sacrificing material and having compensation is different than sacrificing material and getting an immediate return on your investment in the form of winning material or getting a checkmating attack.   Compensation tends to be a bit more of a long-term thing where you are not immediately profiting from the material investment but are instead playing for other advantages that you gain and play with as the game progresses.} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "What is Compensation?"]
[Black "How to Evaluate Positions"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {In order to evaluate whether a material sacrifice is worth the compensation that we may gain, it is important to be able to assess and evaluate positions in an objective manner. When you are looking to evaluate a position, there are four factors that you should consider to help you assess whether the position is better for White, better for Black or equal. The four factors are:   1. King safety   2. Material   3. Piece activity   4. Pawn play   King safety is the first factor in the list. This is because all the other factors don't matter in a position if your king ends up being unsafe enough that you get checkmated. Simply put, checkmate ends the game, and for this reason, king safety should be a priority. If all other things are equal, but our king is safer and less exposed than our opponent's king then we would have the advantage in the position.   Material is the second factor in the list. This is something that many players below master-level give too much importance to. Most players would rather have a disadvantage in all the other factors but be ahead a pawn rather than being down a pawn but having everything else in their favor. As you will come to appreciate throughout this chapter and course, material is not the only factor to think about in positions and being down material but having compensation in other forms can be very powerful.   Piece activity is the third factor in the list. This refers to the usefulness of our pieces compared to our opponent's pieces. If we have open files for our rooks, open diagonals for our bishops, strong outposts for our knights and the ability to invade our opponent's half of the board easily then this can be very powerful. Generally speaking, most gambit openings (including the Benko Gambit) are based around gambiting/sacrificing material and gaining an advantage in piece activity in return.   Pawn play is the fourth factor in the list. This focuses on the placement of the pawns for each player, who has the better pawn structure and who has more space. If your opponent has weak doubled pawns, an isolated pawn or a backward pawn while you have no weak pawns of your own, then this will contribute to you having an advantage in this category.   If you have more control of the center and a space advantage with your pawns then this can also be a good advantage too. This may all sound simple enough, but the tough part of evaluating positions is combining multiple factors together. It is very rare that a position will have three factors equal and a fourth factor in one player's favor. Most of the time, you will find that White has an advantage in some of the factors while Black has an advantage in other factors.   For example: You may be ahead a pawn but have a weak king. You may have the safer king but worse piece activity. You may have the better pawn structure but be down material. And the list goes on.   I think that evaluating a position along a spectrum and having a small or large advantage/disadvantage with each of these factors will push the evaluation bar in your favor or in your opponent's favor.} 1. --
