 {So as we understand now, the material is just one of the factors that go into evaluating a position. It is not the only factor or the most essential factor!   It is important that you don't fall into the wrong way of thinking of evaluating positions purely based on the material count and ignoring the other factors listed earlier.   Now, let's go ahead and get some practice in terms of evaluating positions. I am going to give a sample of positions you will find throughout the course, and we are going to evaluate these positions based on the four factors mentioned in the previous informational.} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "What is Compensation?"]
[Black "Example #1"]
[FEN "1n3rk1/3p1ppp/b4n2/2p5/8/4P3/Pq1B1PPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position? Many people would look at this position and see that we are down a rook for a minor piece, note that we are down two points in material and say that white must be doing well. However, this would be incorrect. Let's make sure we think about all four of the factors:   1. King safety: Our king is much safer than white's king. We have castled and are facing zero attack while white's king has not castled and will find it difficult to castle quickly due to our bishop on a6 aiming down at the f1-square.   2. Material: As noted, we are down the exchange. No getting around this!   3. Piece activity: Our pieces are much more active than white's pieces. Our bishop on a6 cuts through the light squares along the a6-f1 diagonal, our queen is far in white's position bothering them and our knight on f6 is ready to jump to e4 soon. It is true that our rook on f8 and knight on b8 are not doing much right now but White has many more inactive pieces which doesn't help them at all.   4. Pawn play: White has an isolated a-pawn while we have no weak pawns. In terms of a space advantage, we have a pawn on c5 helping us to have a bit more space in the center.Does Black have enough compensation for the exchange? All things considered, even though we are down two points in material, we actually have everything else in our favor. On top of that, it is our move which means that we can improve our position even more right away with the move1...Ne4which threatens to capture the bishop on d2 since white's queen on d1 is overloaded protecting the a1-rook and d2-bishop at the same time. Black has a huge advantage in this position despite the current material deficit. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
