[Black "Example #2"]
[FEN "r3k2r/3p1ppp/q1n2b2/2p5/8/P3PN2/1P2QPPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Both kings are uncastled for the moment, but neither is in much danger.   2. Material: We are down one pawn. Typical for the Benko Gambit!   3. Piece activity: Our bishop on f6 is vastly better than white's bishop on c1. The two knights and queens somewhat cancel each other out.   4. Pawn play: Neither player has a particularly weak pawn structure, but I would say that the pawn on b2 is a bit weaker than any pawn in our half of the board. For a space advantage, our pawn on c5 is giving us a slight edge.   Does black have enough compensation for the pawn? All things considered, the position is relatively balanced, with maybe a very small advantage for white. This is because our superior bishop may not be better enough compared to white's to make up for the extra pawn that white has fully. That being said, this is a position where I would argue that it is easier for black to play since it is not easy for white to develop their bishop without worrying about the b2-pawn. If they cannot activate the bishop then being ahead one pawn won't matter if they are down a three-points bishop! You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
