 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Both kings are pretty safe. Neither side is castled but without queens on the board and a few minor pieces having been traded, neither king is in any danger.   2. Material: We have our usual pawn deficit.   3. Piece activity: Our bishop on h6 is a monster aiming straight through white's position. Also, our rook on a8 is better than white's rook on a1. White's knight on e2 is in the way of their bishop on f1.   4. Pawn play: We have an isolated h-pawn but there is no way for White to attack it. We have the potential for a passed c-pawn with moves such as ...c4-c3. White's a2-pawn is a bit of a target here and needs to be constantly defended.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? Add everything together, and we have a good amount of advantages to make up for our one pawn disadvantage. It is not surprising that the engine gives Black a slight advantage here and the advantage can become more substantial if White doesn't play the move f4 right away. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
