 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: We are castled already while white's king is still in the center. That being said, it is not likely that we will be able to hit white's king anytime soon.   2. Material: Another position where we're down a pawn!   3. Piece activity: Our bishop on g7 is very strong and ties White down to protect the b2-pawn. Our d7-knight can hop into the weak c5-square very soon to harass white's queen. White's knight on d2 is in the way of their c1-bishop.   4. Pawn play: We have an isolated a-pawn while White has a backward b2-pawn that we are currently targeting. White does have more space in the center of the board but they also have weak dark squares that look more like Swiss cheese holes.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? It ends up here that the position is pretty balanced, assuming that White plays the best move Nb3 here. If they play anything else and allow us to play ...Nc5 then we could easily start to take over the advantage. Our pawn deficit is compensated by our good piece activity and the weak b2-pawn target. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
