 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: White's king is very unsafe compared to our castled king.   2. Material: We are down a piece but have one extra pawn. This means we are down two points in material.   3. Piece activity: Other than the rook on a8, all of our pieces are active in the game in some way. And even the inactive a8-rook will go to e8 or d8 soon and become very useful! White's pieces are less active in comparison, especially with neither of their rooks performing any useful function right now.   4. Pawn play: We have a potentially weak backward pawn on c5 that White is hitting with their d3-knight. White has a target in their b2-pawn that could be attacked more later on. We have a space advantage on the queenside with the c5/b4 pawn structure.   Does Black have enough compensation for the one pawn vs piece deficit? Putting everything together, it ends up that Black has a sizable advantage here despite being down two points in material. White's king will have a very difficult time finding any safety while all of our pieces will rain down on the king very soon. We have ideas such as ...Ba4+, ...Rd8 or ...Rae8 and invading down the e-file. The b2-pawn needs protection and the c4-pawn is also potentially a target. White faces a tough road ahead of them to survive this position. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
