 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: White's king is a bit safer than our king due to our f7-pawn missing.   2. Material: We are ahead the exchange (rook for bishop) which is a two-point advantage.   3. Piece activity: Aside from white's g5-knight, none of the other pieces on the board inspire much confidence right now.   4. Pawn play: We have doubled isolated e-pawns that are very weak and easily targeted. White has an isolated d-pawn for themselves that does give them a slight space advantage.   Does White have enough compensation for the exchange? It ends up here that we are in a fairly balanced and equal position with a slight practical edge for White. They are down two points in material but have all the other advantages in their favor. Especially if they can win the e6-pawn at some point (which may be difficult for us to prevent forever) then they will be in even better shape than they are currently. You can see how we got to this position in the clickable variation HERE.} 1. --
