 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Both kings are safe and in no danger.   2. Material: We are down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: We have very active pieces, especially with the bishop pair cutting through white's position. Our rook on e8 is more active than either of white's rooks. Our d7-knight is ready to hop into the e5 or f6-squares, and our queen is hitting the knight on d2, thus requiring White to devote a piece to defending it. White's knight on a5 may hop into the c6-square and be useful. Alternatively, white's d2-knight may go to c4 and target our d6-pawn.   4. Pawn play: White has doubled f-pawns, but the f5-pawn can be traded on g6 anytime. Their b2-pawn needs constant protection, while our d6-pawn may be a slight weakness for us if White can put a knight on c4 to attack it.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? It ends up here that we are in a fairly balanced and equal position despite the one-pawn difference. I would probably give the practical edge to Black here by a little bit since it is slightly difficult to coordinate white's pieces while we can do things like ...Ne5 or double rooks on the e-file. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
