 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Both kings are pretty unsafe. White's king is very exposed and black's king is uncastled and stuck in the center for now.   2. Material: We are ahead three pawns! This isn't super common for the repertoire but it's hard to complain about having more material :-)   3. Piece activity: White's pieces are more active than ours.   4. Pawn play: White has isolated h2 and d5-pawns, while we don't really have any pawn weaknesses. We do have a slight space advantage on the queenside.   Does White have enough compensation for the three pawns? With all this combined together, it ends up that White doesn't have enough compensation here for the three-pawn deficit.   White's best move here is to play Ne6 and try to make use of the weak e6-square and our uncastled king, but objectively we are in good shape as Black. If we were not ahead as much material (for example, if White had an extra pawn on g2) then the game would probably be more balanced. Three pawns are a lot, though! Remember that the amount of compensation you need is related to how much material you are down in the first place. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
