 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Neither king is castled, but White can castle a little bit quicker than we can.   2. Material: We are ahead one pawn.   3. Piece activity: White has a substantial lead in development with two extra pieces and the ability to castle quicker.   4. Pawn play: There are no weak pawns or pawns that would be useful to determine a space advantage here for either player.   Does White have enough compensation for the pawn? Here I would lean towards the answer being no. While it is true that White is ahead in development, it is not terribly difficult for Black to develop their f8-bishop and castle soon.   Also, it is not easy for White to stir up immediate trouble in this position without trading on d5 and giving us an isolated pawn (which would also cost White the bishop pair). Perhaps if White does play Bxd5 then they can claim some compensation but I think Black should be able to weather than short-term problems that White can stir up and be pleasantly better in the long-term. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
