 {White to move. How would we evaluate this position? Let's break it down:   1. King safety: Neither king is castled but it is also not that easy for either player to attack the other king anytime soon.   2. Material: We are ahead one pawn.   3. Piece activity: Both sides have fairly active pieces. Both of our knights are harassing pawns and white's pieces are all relatively well-developed and centralized.   4. Pawn play: White has weak pawns on f4 and a2. We have a weakish pawn on b7 but White cannot capture it anytime soon due to a ...Bb4 pin.   Does White have enough compensation for the pawn? Not really. Because they cannot capture the b7-pawn right away then, they cannot equalize the material. Other than the b7-pawn, we have no weak pawns while white's position has a few more (f4 and a2). This position shows the importance of having targets or weaknesses to attack when determining the level of compensation. Without White having any clear targets in the position and with them being down a pawn with plenty of weaknesses of their own, this combines to show that Black has a sizable advantage here. You can see how we got to this position in the variation HERE.} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "What is Compensation?"]
[Black "How to Play With Compensation"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Now that we understand what compensation is, how to evaluate positions and have seen plenty of examples of these things, the final question is 'how do I play in positions where I have compensation'? It is not enough to simply know that you have compensation. You must also play these positions in accordance with this compensation too!   Generally speaking, compensation falls into two categories that we've seen: short-term compensation or 'dynamic' compensation and long-term compensation or 'static' compensation. Dynamic compensation would be things like a lead in development, attacking chances and the initiative.   These are things that will naturally disappear in a game if you don't use them soon. On the other hand, static compensation includes things such as having the bishop pair, your opponent having weak pawns, having a very strong knight on an outpost or a rook having good control of an open file. These are things that will not disappear naturally without you making some mistake along the way.   If your compensation in a position is more of a dynamic nature, then it is important that you are constantly looking for forcing moves, tactics, ways to pressure your opponent and trying to get the upper hand and end the game quickly (or at least win back the sacrificed material).   Alternatively, if your compensation is more of a static nature, then you do not necessarily need to be in a rush to use the advantages you have. They are not going to disappear anytime soon naturally.   You can play these types of positions a bit more slowly and not feel like you need to crush the opponent quickly. Of course, you should still be looking for tactics and forcing moves even when you have static compensation. Ultimately, playing with compensation requires practice and faith in yourself and your skills. Many players will feel a bit uncomfortable at first when they are playing variations in the course where they are down material without any immediate way to win it back.   However, I think it is a very important skill to be able to play positions with compensation. Getting better at this will open up a lot more opportunities for yourself in your games and make you a much stronger chess player. In the next few informationals you will see a few positions taken from the Model Games chapter. We'll work on evaluating these positions and then you'll be able to see how each position was played in the Model Games chapter.   I wish you all the best as you go through the course and strive to become a compensation master!} 1. --
