 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position?   1. King safety: Neither king is particularly weak or unsafe. Maybe black's king is slightly safer since we can castle anytime we want to whereas White needs to trade queens on a6 before they can castle kingside.   2. Material: We are currently down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: Our pieces are at least slightly more active than white's pieces. Our rook on a8 is helping to target the a2-pawn whereas white's c2-rook is more defensive. Our bishop is aiming into white's half of the board while white's bishop is not doing much. Our knight is a bit more on the queenside helping there compared to white's knight which isn't doing much on f3.   4. Pawn play: Both sides have an isolated pawn on the a-file for White and on the d-file for Black.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? At this point I would say yes but we should definitely focus on winning the a2-pawn at some point in order to equalize things. Compared to the previous example, any advantages we have with king safety and piece activity are much smaller which means the game is fairly equal at this point since we are still down the pawn. You can see the full game HERE.} 1. --
