 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position?   1. King safety: Our king is safe on g8 while white's king may come under some pressure soon from the rook moving to g6 or h6, the e4-knight aiming on the kingside a bit and the bishop on b7 lining up towards the g2-pawn.   2. Material: We are currently down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: Most of our pieces are more active than white's. Our e4-knight is better than their e1-knight and our b7-bishop is a bit better than the e2-bishop. The c1-bishop and b8-knight are not in the game yet and the queens are both relatively useful. The biggest piece difference is going to be the d6-rook compared to white's a1-rook. Our rook has been lifted to the sixth rank and will be very strong once it goes to g6 or h6 soon.   4. Pawn play: Neither side has any weak pawns. We have a little bit more space on the queenside but the game isn't likely to focus on that side of the board in the short-term.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? This will really depend on how much of an attack Black can stir up on the kingside using their lifted rook. If Black is able to create problems then White will be under a lot of pressure. However, if White can defend against the attack and consolidate their position then their extra pawn and bishop pair will give them an edge in the long-term. You can see the full game HERE.} 1. --
