 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position?   1. King safety: Both kings are pretty safe for the moment but white's king may face some trouble in the near future. We may be able to play ...Rg6 and attack the g2-pawn with our rook and b7-bishop but that will take some preparation since the knight on c6 is in the way.  2. Material: We are currently down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: With our lifted rook we do have the piece activity advantage. Our b7-bishop and rook will attack on the kingside soon. We may also be able to put the other bishop on d6 to aim at the kingside too. White's bishops are not very effective right now and their queen is more of a liability than being helpful at all.   4. Pawn play: Neither side has any weak pawns. We have a little bit more space on the queenside but the game isn't likely to focus on that side of the board in the short-term.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? Similar to the previous position, this will depend on how much of an attack Black can stir up on the kingside using their lifted rook. If Black is able to create problems then White will be under a lot of pressure. However, if White can defend against the attack and consolidate their position then their extra pawn and bishop pair will give them an edge in the long-term. While this position and the previous position are similar, they do play out in slightly different ways. You can see the full game HERE.} 1. --
