 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position?   1. King safety: Neither king is particularly weak or safe. In the long-term, it may actually be our king that is a bit weaker since we do not have the option of castling but in the short-term we could see white's king facing trouble since Black has a few more forcing move options here than White does.   2. Material: We are currently down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: Both sides have relatively active pieces but it ends up here that we simply have a higher quantity of active pieces since both of our rooks are in the game whereas white's rooks haven't moved yet.   4. Pawn play: Neither side has any weak pawns. We have more space across the board with the g5-pawn giving more kingside space and the c5-pawn giving more queenside space.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? This will depend on if we can create enough trouble for White that they don't get to castle and keep their king safe. If we are able to put pressure on White before they can get their king out of the center and develop their rooks then we will be in good shape.   In the game Baenziger did a great job of putting maximum pressure on White before they got to complete castle the king and get the rooks into the game. You can see the full game HERE.} 1. --
