 {Black to move. How would we evaluate this position?   1. King safety: We are castled while white's king is still in the center. It is unlikely that they will want to castle queenside since the king would continue to be exposed and if they want to castle kingside then they still need to develop the light-square bishop first.   2. Material: We are currently down one pawn.   3. Piece activity: This is relatively balanced but the queen on d5 is more of a target than being helpful. We may be able to gain a tempo by attacking it and improving our piece activity at the same time.   4. Pawn play: Neither side has any weak pawns. We have more space on the queenside with the c5-pawn while White has more space on the kingside with the e5-pawn.   Does Black have enough compensation for the pawn? Similar to the previous position, this will depend on if we can create enough trouble for White that they don't get to castle and keep their king safe. We have a dynamic advantage with a lead in development and good piece activity. Combine this with the ability to harass white's queen and make forcing moves a bit easier than White can, we should definitely be looking to press these advantages quickly before White can complete their development and castle.   In the game Pogosyan wasn't able to prevent White from castling but was able to gain other long-term advantages along the way that led to them having strong compensation in a more static sense later. You can see the full game HERE.} 1. --
