[Black "5. f3 axb5 6.e4 Qa5+ 7.Bd2 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. f3 {Of the five most common responses to the move 4...a6, we now have the rarest of the five which is the move 5. f3. Grandmaster Maxim Dlugy was not the first person to play this variation(that award is given to D Shadrin in 1957)but did play it many times between the years 1986-1995 and thus this became known as the 'Dlugy Variation'.  Since then, it has been played by many strong grandmasters. The idea behind the move 5. f3 is that White is willing to let Black recapture the pawn on b5 but in return White will build a strong pawn chain with 6. e4. This variation tends to be dynamic in nature, with various pawn sacrifices for Black that we will see throughout this chapter. Let's check it out!} 
5. axb5 {Another popular option is5...e6which leads to a forced variation that results in a very imbalanced material situation with unconventional moves. I prefer to keep the game a bit more double-edged with less memorization required but still good play for Black.} 
6. e4 {White is now threatening Bxb5 as well as e5. There is only one way to deal with this.} 
6. Qa5+ {We give this check to disrupt white's coordination. If they block the check with a piece on d2 then the d5-pawn will not be supported by the queen and it will be more difficult for White to play e5.} 
7. Bd2 {White usually blocks the check with the bishop and counterattacks our queen. The downside of this move is that it blocks white's queen from defending the d5-pawn and makes it so that e5 is harder to play.} 
7. b4 {We don't want to move the queen again so we block with our b-pawn.} 
8. Na3 {Essentially the only move played in this position. White is able to develop their knight and aim at the c4-square due to the pin on the b4-pawn along the diagonal towards our queen.} 
8. e6 {Fitting in with the theme of the chapter, we look to quickly attack and trade off white's d5-pawn which is giving them a space advantage in the center. This move is much more rare than the usual 8...d6 move which is played in this position almost 10 times more than 8...e6. White has to be precise with their next few moves to not get into a worse position quickly.} 
9. Nc4 {White continues with their maneuver.} 
9. Qc7 {We keep the queen as active as possible while still threatening the d5-pawn.} 
10. Bg5 {The only critical move for White. They defend their d5-pawn by opening up the d1-queen while also potentially trading for the knight and doubling our f-pawns. White's immediate idea is to play d6 if we don't stop them.} 
10. d6 {We prevent White from advancing their d-pawn forward and cramping us. Next, we want to play ...Be7 to avoid doubled f-pawns if White doesn't trade on f6 quickly.} 
11. Bxf6 {White doubles our pawns but gives us a strong dark-square bishop.} 
11. gxf6
12. Ne2 {Maneuvering towards the f4-square to put pressure on our e6-pawn.} 
12. Bh6 {We prevent White from playing Nf4 and take firm control of the weak dark squares in their position. Our plan going forward is to play ...O-O, ...Nd7-b6, ...f5 and open the position for our bishops.   Especially our dark-square bishop will be a very strong piece in the game going forward. It is essential to know here that the d6-pawn is not actually in trouble too.} 
13. dxe6 {It looks like we may have blundered the d6-pawn but it is actually not good for White to win the pawn since it will open up the position for our bishops!} 
13. fxe6 {We capture with the f-pawn in order to undouble our pawns and keep the d5-square controlled.} 
14. Nxd6+ {If White is going to win the d6-pawn then they should at least get the queens off the board along the way.} 
14. Ke7
15. Nxc8+
15. Rxc8 {White is up a pawn but in huge trouble here. We immediately threaten to play ...Rd8 followed by invading the d2-square. Another idea is to play ...c4-c3 and create a very dangerous passed c-pawn. Finally, ...Nc6-d4 is also in the air and white's development is very much lacking.} 
