5. axb5 {We should capture on b5. If White doesn't take the pawn then we will play ...b4 and if they do capture on b5 against then we'll play in our computerized Benko-style with ...e6!?} 
6. Nxb5 {This recapture is relatively rare at the master level, considering White will usually capture on a6 if they wanted to hold onto the extra pawn.On the other hand, this response is very common in the u2000 lichess database with 5 times as many games being played this way compared to6.e4. The downside to recapturing on b5 now is that the knight will most likely need to move another time in the near future.  That being said, this move altered the trajectory of the game a bit and forces us to change our set-up.} 
