14. a4
14. Nb3
15. Ra3
15. Nxd2 {We get to eliminate white's dark square bishop and leave ourselves with the bishop pair.} 
16. Qxd2 {White now has a positional threat of b3 which would break apart our pawns.} 
16. Ba6 {We prevent b3 since that would now lose a piece due to ...Bxb5 and the a4-pawn would be pinned.} 
17. Qb4 {White defends the knight and prevents us from castling.} 
17. Qe7 {We offer a queen trade so that our centralized king won't be an issue.} 
18. Qxe7+
18. Kxe7
19. Rfa1
19. e5 {We have good compensation for the pawn with our bishop pair and big central space advantage. If White plays b3 then we can trade pieces on b5, then a3 then play ...c3 and have a strong passed pawn. Otherwise, we'll play ...Rc8 and continue improving our position.} 
