[Black "5. b6 e6 6.Nc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. b6 {This is the most popular way for White to half-accept the Benko Gambit by capturing on b5 but not capturing on a6.   The point of this move is to return the gambited pawn to Black with the idea that Black will not have a half-open a-file which they usually have in the fully accepted variations. This is a legitimate way for White to play but the nice thing about the Benko Gambit is that most of the variations where White doesn't fully accept the gambit tend to leave Black with a very pleasant position.   As I was growing up, one of my friends (who also played the Benko Gambit a lot) and I would always say that if you were able to equalize the material in the Benko Gambit then you were in good shape. This tends to be true with the majority of variations.} 
5. e6 {The third most popular move in the database but also the best move in the position. Playing 5...e6 here is in the spirit of the fully accepted variation where we play ...e6 after White captures the a6-pawn.   The ideas are very similar: We want to break down White's central d5-pawn before recapturing the queenside pawn. Once that pawn has been dealt with then we can continue the game. And on top of that, we won't even be down a pawn in this variation!5...Qxb6The most popular move but it gives White a pleasant position where they get to keep their d5-pawn alive and maintain a nice space advantage.6.Nc3g67.e4d68.Nf3Bg79.Nd2⩲White will gain a tempo with Nc4 in the near future while it will be tougher for us to play ...e6 now since our d6-pawn would become a weakness afterwards. White's position is more pleasant and easy to play here.} 
6. Nc3 {White usually defends the d5-pawn with the knight rather than trading pawns on e6 immediately.} 
6. Nxd5 {We eliminate White's d5-pawn before they can play e4 to reinforce it. Capturing with 6...exd5 first would most likely transpose but by capturing with the knight first we give White less options.} 
7. Nxd5
7. exd5
8. Qxd5
8. Nc6 {Blocking the queen from attacking our a8-rook. These last few moves are pretty much forced but here White has a few different directions they can go. The typical set-up for White is to play e4 or Nf3 (in some order) followed by Bc4, O-O and then developing the dark-square bishop. Be careful though! The move order that White plays is very important to be aware of.} 
9. Nf3 {If White starts with 9. Nf3 then we need to watch out for Ne5 ideas which would threaten checkmate on f7 as well as attacking our pinned knight on c6.} 
9. Rb8 {We sidestep the pin along the diagonal and now our knight is free to move.} 
10. e4 {By playing 9. Nf3 first, White has made us play ...Rb8 compared to the variation with 9. e4 first where we don't need to play ...Rb8 and will develop our kingside bishop first instead. This small change doesn't really cause us any trouble though since we were going to move the rook to b8 at some point anyways in order to control the half-open b-file. Now that White has played e4, we need to be ready to defend f7 after they develop their bishop to c4.} 
10. Be7 {We are ready to castle in order to add additional defense to the f7-pawn if necessary.10...Rxb6?Don't rush to grab the pawn too quickly!11.Bc4±Defending the f7-pawn is a lot more awkward to do now. We will need to play ...Qe7 which blocks in our dark-square bishop or ...Qf6 which leaves our queen very exposed and easy to harass.} 
11. Bc4
11. O-O {Now that we've defended f7 and gotten castled then the next step is to capture the pawn on b6 with the rook followed by putting pressure on White's centralized queen or their queenside b2-pawn. The d4-square can also be useful for us at some point since our knight is immediately aiming at that square whereas White's strong d5-square is much harder for their knight on f3 to access.} 
12. O-O
12. Rxb6 {White has a lot of different options from here but as long as we follow similar ideas in the various lines then we will be fine. The general set-up for Black is to play ...d6, ...Be6, trade light-square bishops, maybe ...Bf6 to apply pressure to White's b2-pawn and then involve the queen and remaining f8-rook  (usually going to e8 or b8 to attack one of white's pawns).} 
13. Qh5
13. d6
14. b3
14. Be6
15. Bxe6
15. fxe6
16. Qg4
16. Qc8
17. Bb2
17. e5 {Locking in our bishop but offering a queen trade, controlling the d4-square more and shutting out White's b2-bishop. Keep in mind that weakening the d5-square doesn't matter too much here since the knight on f3 is a long journey from getting there.} 
18. Qxc8
18. Rxc8
19. Nd2
19. a5 {Next is ...a4 to put pressure on White's queenside pawns and trying to create an isolated pawn for them. The knight will go to d4 soon too. I find Black's position easier to play since after ...a4 we will be able to create a target and it is difficult for White to attack our weak d6-pawn since we can always play ...Nd4 to block off the d-file.} 
