4. cxb5
4. a6
5. b6 {This is the most popular way for White to half-accept the Benko Gambit by capturing on b5 but not capturing on a6.   The point of this move is to return the gambited pawn to Black with the idea that Black will not have a half-open a-file which they usually have in the fully accepted variations. This is a legitimate way for White to play but the nice thing about the Benko Gambit is that most of the variations where White doesn't fully accept the gambit tend to leave Black with a very pleasant position.   As I was growing up, one of my friends (who also played the Benko Gambit a lot) and I would always say that if you were able to equalize the material in the Benko Gambit then you were in good shape. This tends to be true with the majority of variations.} 
5. e6 {The third most popular move in the database but also the best move in the position. Playing 5...e6 here is in the spirit of the fully accepted variation where we play ...e6 after White captures the a6-pawn.   The ideas are very similar: We want to break down White's central d5-pawn before recapturing the queenside pawn. Once that pawn has been dealt with then we can continue the game. And on top of that, we won't even be down a pawn in this variation!5...Qxb6The most popular move but it gives White a pleasant position where they get to keep their d5-pawn alive and maintain a nice space advantage.6.Nc3g67.e4d68.Nf3Bg79.Nd2⩲White will gain a tempo with Nc4 in the near future while it will be tougher for us to play ...e6 now since our d6-pawn would become a weakness afterwards. White's position is more pleasant and easy to play here.} 
6. Nc3 {White usually defends the d5-pawn with the knight rather than trading pawns on e6 immediately.} 
6. Nxd5 {We eliminate White's d5-pawn before they can play e4 to reinforce it. Capturing with 6...exd5 first would most likely transpose but by capturing with the knight first we give White less options.} 
7. Nxd5
7. exd5
8. Qxd5
8. Nc6 {Blocking the queen from attacking our a8-rook. These last few moves are pretty much forced but here White has a few different directions they can go. The typical set-up for White is to play e4 or Nf3 (in some order) followed by Bc4, O-O and then developing the dark-square bishop. Be careful though! The move order that White plays is very important to be aware of.} 
9. Nf3 {If White starts with 9. Nf3 then we need to watch out for Ne5 ideas which would threaten checkmate on f7 as well as attacking our pinned knight on c6.} 
9. Rb8 {We sidestep the pin along the diagonal and now our knight is free to move.} 
10. e4 {By playing 9. Nf3 first, White has made us play ...Rb8 compared to the variation with 9. e4 first where we don't need to play ...Rb8 and will develop our kingside bishop first instead. This small change doesn't really cause us any trouble though since we were going to move the rook to b8 at some point anyways in order to control the half-open b-file. Now that White has played e4, we need to be ready to defend f7 after they develop their bishop to c4.} 
10. Be7 {We are ready to castle in order to add additional defense to the f7-pawn if necessary.10...Rxb6?Don't rush to grab the pawn too quickly!11.Bc4±Defending the f7-pawn is a lot more awkward to do now. We will need to play ...Qe7 which blocks in our dark-square bishop or ...Qf6 which leaves our queen very exposed and easy to harass.} 
11. Bc4
11. O-O {Now that we've defended f7 and gotten castled then the next step is to capture the pawn on b6 with the rook followed by putting pressure on White's centralized queen or their queenside b2-pawn. The d4-square can also be useful for us at some point since our knight is immediately aiming at that square whereas White's strong d5-square is much harder for their knight on f3 to access.} 
12. O-O
12. Rxb6 {White has a lot of different options from here but as long as we follow similar ideas in the various lines then we will be fine. The general set-up for Black is to play ...d6, ...Be6, trade light-square bishops, maybe ...Bf6 to apply pressure to White's b2-pawn and then involve the queen and remaining f8-rook  (usually going to e8 or b8 to attack one of white's pawns).} 
13. b3 {White gets their b2-pawn to a safer location but will run into trouble with their light-square bishop running low on squares.} 
13. Na5 {Because the queen is still on d5, then the square is not available for white's bishop to move to.} 
14. Be2
14. Bb7
15. Qd3
15. Re6 {A creative rook lift to apply more pressure to white's e4-pawn. White has some trouble here dealing with black's piece activity and has to be very careful to not fall apart soon.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Benko Gambit Half/Fully Accepted"]
[Black "5. bxa6 e6 6.Nc3 exd5 7.Nxd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. bxa6 {Historically, the Benko Gambit has been played with Black playing5...Bxa6immediately here in order to make it difficult for White to play the move e4 without allowing a trade of light-square bishops and costing White their ability to castle (due to Kxf1 usually occuring).  Over time though, there have been problems with this way of playing due to White having found a strong set-up of their pawns and pieces that shuts down a lot of Black's counterplay on the queenside. If Black isn't able to get good counterplay, then we will simply be down a pawn and in rough shape. You can find more information on this particular variation in the informational HERE.
  As time went on, playing the move5...g6became the main line of the opening where Black delays the capture on a6, instead preferring to develop the kingside pieces first and only capturing the pawn on a6 later at a more helpful time. This way of playing has overtaken5...Bxa6as the main way to play nowadays.} 
5. e6 {Rather than playing5...Bxa6or5...g6, in this course I am recommending the relatively rare option of playing5...e6. At the time of writing, this move has only about 700 games in the ChessBase online database compared to5...Bxa6and5...g6having about 12,000games each. This move will come as a surprise for the majority of players since they will know what to do against5...Bxa6or5...g6but here we get to throw them off first! This move is not just a 'surprise-factor' move, though.  According to modern engines (Stockfish 15 NNUE is what I'm using for the moment),5...e6is actually the best move in the position by a bit and takes the game in a whole different direction than the more common5...Bxa6or5...g6variations. A direction that you will be well prepared for! Another thing to note is that this opening choice is bolstered by a lot of correspondence games which gives more credence to variation.  Alright, so enough about the evaluation and surprise factor. What is the point of this5...e6move? The idea here is simple: We want to break down White's central d5-pawn before they are able to reinforce it with e4. Without White's d5-pawn, then it will be easier for us to develop our queenside knight to c6, and fight for control of the d4-square and we can also use the half-open e-file in many variations. The spirit of the opening remains the same, though: We will prioritise piece activity as well as open lines and files in the center+queenside areas of the board in order to put our opponent under a lot of pressure while we have all the fun. Let's see how we'll do that!5...g66.Nc3Bg77.e4O-OThis is the more modern way of playing the Benko Gambit nowadays. Black doesn't recapture the pawn on a6 yet but instead prefers rapid development with the idea to play ...Qa5 next and capture the pawn on a6 at a more convenient time.8.a7±This has been found to be the critical move for White in this version of the Benko Gambit.  White knows they are going to lose the a-pawn but wants Black to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. Nc3 {The most common move. White defends their d5-pawn rather than trading on e6. If given the chance, White will play the move e4 next to further defend their d5-pawn. We cannot allow this!} 
6. exd5 {We trade on d5 immediately so that White cannot reinforce the pawn with e4.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Be7 {The second-most played move in this variation but my preference. We are simply accelerating our kingside development and waiting for White to decide on their set-up. We do not mind if White trades the knight for the bishop on e7 since this will allow us to develop the queen a bit and White will have lost a lot of time moving the knight a third time in the opening to capture a bishop that has only moved once.} 
8. Bf4 {White develops their light-square bishop and threatens Nc7+. The downside to this move is that the bishop ends up being a bit misplaced in the resulting middlegames.} 
8. Nxd5
9. Qxd5
9. Nc6 {We block off the attack on our rook while developing the knight. Next we want to castle kingside and then capture on a6 with our bishop.} 
10. e4 {The pawn on e4 will make it more difficult for us to play ...d5 later but the upside is that the d4-square is weaker and easier for us to use.} 
10. O-O
11. Nf3
11. Qb6 {We harass the b2-pawn because White developed their c1-bishop early in the game.} 
12. Qd2
12. Bf6 {We continue to attack the b2-pawn while White is behind in kingside development.} 
13. e5 {White blocks off the diagonal towards the b2-pawn.} 
13. Re8 {Pinning the e-pawn and giving White trouble.} 
14. Be2 {White cannot afford to waste more time defending the e5-pawn and needs to focus on getting castled as soon as possible.} 
14. Bxa6 {We capture the a6-pawn instead of the e5-pawn since the pin along the e-file is still there.} 
15. O-O
15. Bxe2
16. Qxe2
16. d6 {We will win the e5-pawn next move and equalize material along with having consistent pressure on the queenside with the half-open files. Playing ...Nd4 will be useful at some point too.} 
