 to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. Nc3 {The most common move. White defends their d5-pawn rather than trading on e6. If given the chance, White will play the move e4 next to further defend their d5-pawn. We cannot allow this!} 
6. exd5 {We trade on d5 immediately so that White cannot reinforce the pawn with e4.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Be7 {The second-most played move in this variation but my preference. We are simply accelerating our kingside development and waiting for White to decide on their set-up. We do not mind if White trades the knight for the bishop on e7 since this will allow us to develop the queen a bit and White will have lost a lot of time moving the knight a third time in the opening to capture a bishop that has only moved once.} 
8. Nxe7 {White gains the bishop pair but will be behind in development for a while.} 
8. Qxe7
9. e3 {White opens up their light-square bishop but blocks in the dark-square bishop.} 
9. O-O
10. Nf3 {Continuing to develop the kingside pieces.} 
10. Rxa6 {I like this creative capture. We don't mind sacrificing the exchange if it means White has to part with their light-square bishop and have trouble castling.} 
11. Bxa6 {This is incredibly risky for White to play but if White knows the precise follow-up then they may accept this exchange sacrifice.} 
11. Bxa6
12. Ng1 {The only good move for White! The knight is headed towards the e2-square in order to block off the bishop's diagonal and allow White to castle.} 
12. Qe4 {Black needs to act quickly to use their lead in development and put pressure on White before they can castle. We now threaten the g2-pawn and provoke some weaknesses in white's position.} 
13. f3 {13.Qf3??White tries to trade queens but will get into big trouble.13...Qb4+14.Bd2Qxb215.Qd1Ne4-+Black is down the exchange but has tremendous compensation (and a huge advantage) with a big lead in development, active pieces, consistent threats and a safer king.} 
13. Qh4+
14. g3
14. Qh5 {We keep pressure on the f3-pawn so that White cannot play Ne2.} 
15. Kf2 {White reinforces the f3-pawn and wants to play Ne2 next.} 
15. Bb7 {We continue to keep an eye on the f3-pawn and keep preventing white's kingside development. We are down the exchange and a pawn but have a lot of pressure on white's position, a big lead in development and the safer king. Next we have ideas like ...Ne4+ (taking advantage of the pinned f3-pawn), ...Nc6-e5 and ...Re8.} 
