1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. e3 {White opens up their f1-bishop to defend the c4-pawn.} 
4. b4 {Similar to many of the other variations, we push our pawn to b4 and will play the resulting pawn structure. Usually White will play e3-e4 later on which means they will lose a tempo.} 
5. b3 {White prepares to fianchetto their bishop since the e3-pawn is blocking its main diagonal. The drawback to this is that it delays white's kingside development which means we will be able to play ...e6 later with strong effect opening the center of the board.} 
5. g6 {We will challenge the bishop on the diagonal.} 
6. Bb2
6. Bg7
7. Nd2
7. O-O
8. Ngf3 {White develops the knight first but this will lead to some tactical possibilities if White isn't careful.} 
8. e6 {Chipping away at white's center as usual.} 
9. e4 {This is the typical response from White but it took two moves to play this move and we can open the center right away. This is a recipe for disaster for White.} 
9. exd5
10. cxd5 {Recapturing with the e-pawn would run into ...Re8+ and ...Qe7 which would prevent White from castling.} 
10. Nxe4 {We can immediately capture the pawn in the center and win material due to tactics involving the undefended bishop on b2!} 
11. Bxg7 {It looks like we've been fooled since our rook on f8 and knight on e4 are both attacked...} 
11. Re8 {But we can create our own counterattack! We save the rook and set up discovered attacks with our knight such as ...Nc3+ hitting the queen. We are also threatening the simple ...Kxg7 capture too.} 
12. Be5 {White may try to keep their extra material but this will backfire for them.} 
12. Nc3 {Attacking white's queen first and pinning the bishop on e5.} 
13. Qc2
