1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Nf3 {The most popular way to decline the Benko Gambit. White decides to not capture on b5 and instead waits for us to make a decision regarding our b-pawn.   The drawback to this move is that it blocks the f-pawn and doesn't put any pressure on us and lets us make a free move. For this reason, in the relevant theory chapter we will see more a3 advances from White and in the Qc2 chapter we will see more f4 advances.} 
4. b4 {In this particular variation, we are going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkward for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions! Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6, play ...a5 and push our e-pawn to e6 (to attack white's d5-pawn) or e5 (to close the center).} 
5. a3 {The most common response but by a very small margin. White challenges our b4-pawn and hopes that we will capture on a3 so that the c3-square will open up for White's knight. We are pretty much never going to be capturing on a3 and will almost always leave the pawn on b4 and wait for White to make the trade.} 
5. g6 {It's best for us to stick to the usual development scheme here. A lot of the time we will respond to a3 with ...a5 but usually that would be after we have developed the kingside a bit more.} 
6. axb4 {White trades on b4 which releases their c4-pawn to advance forward in the future.} 
6. cxb4 {White may try to use their c-pawn in some cases but we may also be able to use the weak c5-square to maneuver a knight to one day.} 
7. Bd2 {White threatens the b4-pawn but blocks the d2-square from the knight.} 
7. Na6
8. g3 {Since the e-pawn isn't going to e4 anytime soon, White decides to develop their light-squared bishop to g2.} 
8. Bg7
9. Bg2
9. Ne4 {We can immediately take advantage of White's bishop not defending their b2-pawn.} 
10. Qc2
10. Nxd2
11. Nbxd2
11. Nc5 {We have the pair of bishops, a good knight on c5 and a very pleasant position. Next we'll castle kingside, play ...d6, ...a5 and maybe later play ...e6 to open the center a bit more.} 
