5. f3 {There is an important move for Black to know here.} 
5. Bd6 {Another example of ignoring our opponent's threat and making our own!} 
6. Bxd6
6. Nxd6
7. e4
7. b5 {Gaining space on the queenside and making sure White cannot play c4 easily.} 
8. Nc3 {If White instead tries8.e5?then after8...Nf5they already face trouble dealing with ...Qh4+ and ...Ne3 threats.} 
8. b4
9. Na4
9. Qc7
10. c3
10. bxc3
11. Nxc3
11. O-O {This is one of the more unique configurations of pieces you will see in this repertoire (knight on d6 blocking our own d7-pawn) but our position is perfectly fine here. We can look to play ...Ba6 to trade bishops or ...Na6 to develop our knight and we want to play around the queenside with ...c4, ...Na6-c5, ...Rb8, etc. White's dark squares are also a bit weak. If White ever plays e5 then we will play ...Nf5 in response.} 
