2. Bf4 {The London System is a very solid opening that has become mainstream over the past years. White usually looks to set up a triangle of pawns from f2-e3-d4-c3-b2 with their pieces typically being developed with Bf4, Nf3, Bd3, Nbd2 in some order. This opening is tough to crack and get any objective advantage against White's best play.   However, White usually plays the opening in a non-ambitious way and doesn't really put much pressure on Black until the middlegame arises. With this in mind, we are actually going to be trying to put pressure on White earlier in the game so that we can distract them from their typical autopilot set-up.} 
2. c5 {Immediately striking at the center using our typical 2...c5 pawn break. White usually plays e3 here but there are a few other options for us to be ready to play against.} 
3. e3 {White's most popular move, reinforcing the d4-pawn and looking to get the typical London System pawn triangle going.} 
3. Qb6
4. b3 {As we've seen in plenty of other lines, playing b3 is almost never a good way to respond to the attack on the b-pawn. Fortunately for us, this is the most popular move in the U2000 lichess database here!} 
4. g6
5. Nf3
5. Bg7
6. c3
6. O-O
7. Bd3
7. Nc6
8. O-O
8. Nh5
9. Bg5
9. d5 {The move order doesn't really matter a ton but we are doing all the same things as the mainline. Next, we will try to push through with ...e5 if possible in order to open up the a1-h8 diagonal for our dark-squared bishop.} 
