2. Nf3
2. c5
3. c3 {Many people who play the London System will try to get to their normal set-up (d4, Nf3, Bf4) with this move order starting with 2. Nf3. This move order is a bit tougher for us to crack with our 2...c5 advance since playing something like ...Qb6 here doesn't make any sense due to the b2-pawn still being defended. That being said, I think I've still come up with a good way to combat the London system set-up that White may go for.} 
3. d5
4. Bf4 {White gets a version of the London System that is a bit different from what is recommended in the main London System chapter. The main difference is due to the pawns being on ...d5 and c3. That being said, Black is doing well in this version of things as long as we go for quick play against White's b2-pawn soon.} 
4. Qb6 {Immediately threatening to capture on b2 since White's bishop is no longer defending the pawn.} 
5. Qb3 {White's most popular location for the queen to defend against the threat on b2.} 
5. Nc6 {We don't mind leaving the tension between the queens for now. We will only capture on b3 if we can give White isolated pawns. White usually doesn't want to capture us on b6 either since it will open up our a8-rook. We will usually play ...c4 next to force white's queen to make a decision.} 
6. e3 {White's most popular move but already a bit of a mistake! Now we get a pleasant advantage due to a typical idea.} 
6. c4
7. Qxb6 {Trading queens on b6 will give Black an advantageous pawn structure.} 
7. axb6 {Black is better now despite having doubled b-pawns. These pawns will be useful in the near future since we can quickly play ...b5-b4 to chip away at white's b2-d4 pawn chain. Our rook is also open on the a-file now.} 
8. Nbd2 {This doesn't prevent us from carrying out our ...b5-b4 plan.} 
8. b5
9. Be2
9. e6 {Since White is doing nothing to slow down ...b4, we can be extra precise and be ready to capture back on b4 with our dark-square bishop. It is best for us to prioritize this plan as soon as possible since any delay may give White the chance to prevent ...b4 from happening. For example, if we play9...Bf5first then after10.O-Oe6White can play11.a3and we will not be able to get in the ...b4 pawn break anymore.} 
10. O-O
10. b4 {We need to strike now since White was threatening to play a3 shutting down our pawn break. This works for White since castling defends the rook on a1 and the a3-pawn would not be pinned.   Our general plan here is to play ...b5, trade on c3 and then play ...b4 a second time. Once the pawn chain is broken down then we can start to pick away at white's weak queenside pawns and have a passed c-pawn ourselves.} 
