1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5
3. d5 {As we've seen throughout the course, almost all of the critical lines for White after we play ...c5 involve them advancing forward with their pawn to d5 and here it is no different.   White sidesteps our c-pawn and gains space in the center of the board. Rather than having the pawn on c4, they instead have a knight on f3 which does change things a bit.} 
3. b5 {I recommend playing in our typical Benko-style even though white's pawn is not on c4 yet. With our ...b5 advance here we are gaining queenside space and are ready to transpose into our Benko Gambit Declined chapters if White was to play c4 here. Instead, the more critical attempts for White involve playing for an early e4 advance and leaving their pawn off the c4-square in the meantime.} 
4. e3 {White advances the e-pawn but blocks in the c1-bishop and doesn't get the pawn to e4 quickly.} 
4. b4
5. Bc4
5. e6 {Normally we would play ...g6 and ...Bg7 here but because White doesn't have the option of playing c4, we can immediately hit the d5-pawn and force White to trade off their central pawn soon.} 
6. O-O
6. Bb7 {Forcing White to trade on e6 or else lose a pawn.} 
7. dxe6
7. fxe6 {White's bishop is awkwardly placed since it will get hit with ...d5 soon. It is probably best for us to play ...Be7 and ...O-O before ...d5 though so that Bb5 doesn't come with a check.} 
