 to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. dxe6 {White decides to trade their d5-pawn for our f7-pawn (those are the two pawns that disappear from the board) and allow us to have two pawns in the central files. This takes the game in a bit of a different direction compared to6.Nc3due to the difference in pawn structures.} 
6. fxe6 {We recapture with the f-pawn in order to avoid a queen trade and to keep an extra pawn in the central files.} 
7. Nc3 {White wants to play e4 to get space in the center.} 
7. Bxa6 {Since White hasn't moved their e-pawn yet, we can capture on a6 and pin the pawn. If it moves then we are happy to trade on f1 and then White would not be able to castle.} 
8. e4
8. Bxf1
9. Kxf1
9. Nc6 {White has been able to get their pawn in the center but at a cost. They cannot castle anymore and the d4-square is a weakness.} 
10. Nf3
10. Be7
11. g3 {White prepares to get their king to a safer square on g2.11.e5?!Advancing the e-pawn puts it into a vulnerable location.11...Ng412.Qe2Qb8This square is best to attack the pawn from. Playing ...Qc7 would run into Nb5 jumps. If White plays Bf4 to defend the pawn, then we can castle kingside with a tempo on the bishop and attack down the f-file. Black is in good shape here, with strong compensation for the pawn.} 
11. O-O
12. Kg2
12. Qb6 {We have strong compensation for the pawn due to our active pieces and pressure down the files. We can play ...Nd4 next to trade off white's f3-knight and continue to pressure down the f-file towards the f2-pawn. White's bishop on c1 cannot develop yet either due to our pressure on the b2-pawn.} 
