 to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. a7 {This a7 pawn push is a good move in some of the mainline5...g6versions of the Benko Gambit but against5...e6it loses a lot of its appeal. White wants us to capture on a7 so that he can gain a tempo with Nb5 later but this doesn't matter to us much with the center opening up.} 
6. Rxa7
7. dxe6 {The only good way to deal with the tension between the central pawns at this point.7.Nc3?!Playing Nc3 after wasting a move forcing us to capture the a-pawn doesn't make much sense.  We're pretty much a move ahead of a lot of the main variations, and without the rook on a8 then there are no pins along the h1-a8 diagonal to be worried about.7...Nxd58.Nxd5exd59.Qxd5Nc6⩱Because the knight isn't pinned, we now have ideas of playing ...Nd4 or ...Nb4 to target the c2-square. The computer recommends the move Qd1 and if that's the case, then we don't need to look further at this variation.} 
7. fxe6
8. Nc3
8. Ba6 {A lot of our play will be similar to the variations where White doesn't include the move a7.} 
9. Nf3
9. Nc6
10. g3
10. Be7
11. Bg2
11. O-O
12. O-O
12. d5 {We have our typical compensation for the pawn with a space advantage and active pieces along with the half-open files on the queenside.} 
