6. e4 {This defends the d5-pawn but loses the e-pawn in return.} 
6. Nxe4 {We have to be a bit precise with our next few moves but if we are, then we'll emerge with a pleasant advantage.} 
7. dxe6 {White sets their first 'trap' with this capture.} 
7. fxe6 {We must take with the f-pawn in order to avoid a queen fork on a4.7...dxe6??8.Qa4++-Loses the knight.} 
