9. Nc3 {The most popular move. White wants to play e5 to attack our knight which doesn't have that many good places to move.9.e5?!Nxd510.Qxd5Nc6You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games here.} 
9. Nxa6 {Wait a second... This doesn't seem to stop e5. What's the idea here?} 
10. e5
10. Bb7 {A piece sacrifice! This sacrifice is completely sound and based on principle: White is not developing their pieces or castling so we should be looking to accelerate our own development, open the center and attack their king. We are willing to give up the knight on f6 in order to open the e-file to help our attack. This move has been played in five correspondence games so far and only one over-the-board game. Maybe you'll be the next one to play it in your game!} 
11. exf6
11. Bxf6 {White's pieces are all sleeping while ours are exerting tremendous pressure against their position. Look at our bishops!} 
12. Bc4 {White may develop the light-square bishop first and hope to play Ne2 instead of Nf3. They are also making it more difficult for us to play ...d5. Our next move works towards achieving this idea.} 
12. Nb4 {Working to play ...d5 next.12...Bxg2?!Going after material here is not the main goal. White is happy to give up the exchange and end up having two minor pieces against one of our rooks.13.Bd5Re8+14.Nge2Bxh115.Bxh1⩲With two minor pieces against our rook White is doing fine here. It is also much more difficult for us to attack their king without the light-square bishop, and the d-pawn is unable to get to d4 easily.} 
13. Nge2
13. d5
14. Bb5
14. d4 {Here comes the bulldozer d-pawn!} 
15. O-O {White's only good move is to give the piece back.} 
15. dxc3
16. Nxc3
16. Bxc3
17. bxc3
17. Nxa2 {We have equalized the material and threaten the c3-pawn. White's bishop pair doesn't give them enough of an edge for us to be concerned at all and the position is balanced.It’s good to note that if White tries to trap our knight with18.Bb2then we can play18...Qg5!(threatening mate on g2) followed by ...Rfd8 and continued pressure along the center and kingside part of the board to distract White from attacking our knight. If White tries18.Bd2instead then we can play18...Qd5(threatening mate again) followed by ...Rfd8 once more.} 
