12. d5 {It is VERY important for us to get our d-pawn up to d4 as quickly as possible. Delaying this would hurt our attack dramatically. This is the only good move for us in the position.12...Re8+??This looks like a very normal check to give but it actually helps White to get closer to castling.13.Be2+-We don't really have a great way to continue attacking from here, and White will castle next move or maybe play Be3 first then castle.} 
13. Be2
13. d4 {We continue to shove the d-pawn down the board.} 
14. Nb5
14. Nb4 {Now ...d3 is the threat.} 
15. Bc4
15. Re8+ {Only now do we check the king when there is not a good way to block the check.} 
16. Kf1
16. d3 {I'm going to cut the line here because memorization is not necessary anymore.   It is surely a double-edged position with White having an extra piece but Black has a big initiative and White had to be very precise to get to this position in the first place. We have ideas of playing ...Nc2, ...Re2 or ...Re4 and white's pieces are all a bit soft and easy to harass. White's king is also unable to castle which means the h1-rook will take a while to get into the game.   If you don't like the look of this position then I may recommend the alternative option of 8...Nxd5 though you will be missing out on a lot of fun!} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Benko Gambit Fully Accepted 5...e6 - 7…Be7 Mainline"]
[Black "5...e6 6.Nc3 exd5 7.Nxd5 Be7 8.e4 [8...Nxd5 Alternative] #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. bxa6 {Historically, the Benko Gambit has been played with Black playing5...Bxa6immediately here in order to make it difficult for White to play the move e4 without allowing a trade of light-square bishops and costing White their ability to castle (due to Kxf1 usually occuring).  Over time though, there have been problems with this way of playing due to White having found a strong set-up of their pawns and pieces that shuts down a lot of Black's counterplay on the queenside. If Black isn't able to get good counterplay, then we will simply be down a pawn and in rough shape. You can find more information on this particular variation in the informational HERE.
  As time went on, playing the move5...g6became the main line of the opening where Black delays the capture on a6, instead preferring to develop the kingside pieces first and only capturing the pawn on a6 later at a more helpful time. This way of playing has overtaken5...Bxa6as the main way to play nowadays.} 
5. e6 {Rather than playing5...Bxa6or5...g6, in this course I am recommending the relatively rare option of playing5...e6. At the time of writing, this move has only about 700 games in the ChessBase online database compared to5...Bxa6and5...g6having about 12,000games each. This move will come as a surprise for the majority of players since they will know what to do against5...Bxa6or5...g6but here we get to throw them off first! This move is not just a 'surprise-factor' move, though.  According to modern engines (Stockfish 15 NNUE is what I'm using for the moment),5...e6is actually the best move in the position by a bit and takes the game in a whole different direction than the more common5...Bxa6or5...g6variations. A direction that you will be well prepared for! Another thing to note is that this opening choice is bolstered by a lot of correspondence games which gives more credence to variation.  Alright, so enough about the evaluation and surprise factor. What is the point of this5...e6move? The idea here is simple: We want to break down White's central d5-pawn before they are able to reinforce it with e4. Without White's d5-pawn, then it will be easier for us to develop our queenside knight to c6, and fight for control of the d4-square and we can also use the half-open e-file in many variations. The spirit of the opening remains the same, though: We will prioritise piece activity as well as open lines and files in the center+queenside areas of the board in order to put our opponent under a lot of pressure while we have all the fun. Let's see how we'll do that!5...g66.Nc3Bg77.e4O-OThis is the more modern way of playing the Benko Gambit nowadays. Black doesn't recapture the pawn on a6 yet but instead prefers rapid development with the idea to play ...Qa5 next and capture the pawn on a6 at a more convenient time.8.a7±This has been found to be the critical move for White in this version of the Benko Gambit.  White knows they are going to lose the a-pawn but wants Black to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. Nc3 {The most common move. White defends their d5-pawn rather than trading on e6. If given the chance, White will play the move e4 next to further defend their d5-pawn. We cannot allow this!} 
6. exd5 {We trade on d5 immediately so that White cannot reinforce the pawn with e4.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Be7 {The second-most played move in this variation but my preference. We are simply accelerating our kingside development and waiting for White to decide on their set-up. We do not mind if White trades the knight for the bishop on e7 since this will allow us to develop the queen a bit and White will have lost a lot of time moving the knight a third time in the opening to capture a bishop that has only moved once.} 
8. e4 {White tries to reinforce their knight on d5 but this only makes the e4-pawn a target after we castle.} 
8. Nxd5 {If you want to avoid the crazy (but fun!) piece sacrifice variations that occur after8...O-O9.Nc3then this is an alternative line that is fine for Black.8...Nxe4??Capturing the e4-pawn immediately will get us into a lot of trouble.9.Qf3!White lines up towards our knight on e4 and rook on a8.9...Nd610.Be3Now, the threat is Nxe7 and Qxa8.10...Nc611.Bxc5Bxa612.Bxa6Rxa613.Qe2Nb814.Nf3+-White has a lead in development, an extra pawn, a better pawn structure and much better piece activity. This is not what we want from this opening.} 
9. exd5 {This isolated d-pawn structure tends to not be ideal for White.} 
9. O-O
10. Nf3
10. d6
11. Be2
11. Nxa6 {We capture with the knight since we want to play ...Nb4 along with ...Bb7 and attack the d5 and a2-pawns. Playing ...Bf5 with the knight on b4 may also be useful in order to access the c2-square.} 
12. O-O
12. Nb4
13. a3
13. Bf6 {We can keep the bishop on c8 for the moment in order to be flexible. If White plays Rb1 to break the pin, then ...Bf5 will harass the rook.} 
14. Bc4
14. Bf5 {Since White has kept the d5-pawn secured, we aim towards the queenside light-squares instead. It is a bit awkward for White to develop their pieces now since the dark-square bishop needs to defend the b2-pawn, the f1-rook cannot go to e1 due to the ...Nc2 fork, the knight on f3 has no good place to move to and the bishop on c4 should be keeping an eye on the d5-pawn as well as the d3-square. We have full compensation for the pawn and will play ...h6 (to prevent Bg5/Ng5), ...Re8, ...Qb6 and keep pressure on White.} 
