8. Nxd5 {If you want to avoid the crazy (but fun!) piece sacrifice variations that occur after8...O-O9.Nc3then this is an alternative line that is fine for Black.8...Nxe4??Capturing the e4-pawn immediately will get us into a lot of trouble.9.Qf3!White lines up towards our knight on e4 and rook on a8.9...Nd610.Be3Now, the threat is Nxe7 and Qxa8.10...Nc611.Bxc5Bxa612.Bxa6Rxa613.Qe2Nb814.Nf3+-White has a lead in development, an extra pawn, a better pawn structure and much better piece activity. This is not what we want from this opening.} 
9. Qxd5
9. Nc6
10. Nf3
10. Bxa6
11. Bxa6 {11.Bd2White may wait for us to make the capture on f1 first but this will simply transpose.11...Qb612.Bc3O-O13.Bxa6Qxa6transposes back to 11.Bxa6 Qa5+.} 
11. Qa5+ {A typical idea to end up with the queen on a6 rather than the rook. The queen will make castling difficult for White.} 
12. Bd2
12. Qxa6
13. Bc3
13. O-O {We're willing to sacrifice the d7-pawn for accelerated development.} 
14. Nd2 {14.Qxd7?Capturing a central pawn like this is greedy when you're behind in development and the king isn't safe. White is only helping us by opening up the d-file.14...Rfd815.Qg4Nd416.Nxd4cxd417.Bd2Rdb8∓White will lose a queenside pawn very soon.} 
14. Nb4
15. Bxb4
15. cxb4
16. Nc4 {White tries to block up the f1-a6 diagonal in order to castle but we can keep up the pressure.} 
16. b3
17. O-O
17. bxa2
18. Na3
18. Rfb8 {We have all the typical pressure against white's queenside and have good play here, even after losing the a2-pawn.} 
