7. Nxd5
7. Be7 {The second-most played move in this variation but my preference. We are simply accelerating our kingside development and waiting for White to decide on their set-up. We do not mind if White trades the knight for the bishop on e7 since this will allow us to develop the queen a bit and White will have lost a lot of time moving the knight a third time in the opening to capture a bishop that has only moved once.} 
8. Bf4 {White develops their light-square bishop and threatens Nc7+. The downside to this move is that the bishop ends up being a bit misplaced in the resulting middlegames.} 
8. Nxd5
9. Qxd5
9. Nc6 {We block off the attack on our rook while developing the knight. Next we want to castle kingside and then capture on a6 with our bishop.} 
10. Nf3
10. O-O
11. e3 {If White puts their pawn on e3 instead of e4 then they do control the d4-square better but we can play ...d5 easier as well.} 
11. Qb6 {We can target the b2-pawn quickly since the bishop is no longer on c1.} 
12. Qd2 {This seems like a reasonable defense but there is a problem with it.} 
12. c4 {Now ... Bb4 pinning the queen is a threat.} 
13. a3
13. d5 {This pawn cannot be captured unless White is willing to let us take on b2 and blast open the center. When White is behind on development like they are here, this would be deadly for them.} 
14. Be2
14. Bf6 {We target the b2-pawn which cannot be defended easily. If White plays Rb1 then we can play ...Bf5 to hit the rook. Notice in this variation how we focus on the b2-pawn and don't bother taking back on a6 yet. The pawn on a6 is not going anywhere and we can capture it later at our leisure.} 
