11. Nc6
12. Be2 {White should probably still continue to avoid winning the exchange since the light-squares will become eternally weak.} 
12. d5 {And we should continue to be okay with leaving our rook on a6! There is no need to retreat it with our tail between our legs.} 
13. O-O
13. Ne4 {We've already gone this far and there is no going back! We plan to play ...Ne5 and then finally get the rook over to h6 or g6. We can also play ...c4 at any point to block off the attack on our rook and attack white's queen at the same time.13...Ra8Since White has now castled and sacrificed the exchange will not prevent them from castling, if you want to finally retreat the rook and avoid losing material then I won't fault you now. This isn't the best move but it is a safe option.} 
14. Qxd5 {White decides to grab a second pawn rather than the exchange. However, this allows the rook to lift to the kingside and we get to have all the fun!} 
14. Nb4
15. Qb3
15. Rg6 {Black has a ton of compensation for the two pawns. We have threats against the kingside (...Bh3), pressure on the queenside (...Be6 hits the queen and a2-pawn) and White has to be careful going forward from here.} 
