 to capture it with the rook on a7 so that a future Nb5 move will gain a tempo on the rook. White scores about 62% from this position and the computers confirm that they are doing well here. With that being said, this variation and way of playing the opening is very interesting. However, it will not be the recommendation in this course.} 
6. Nc3 {The most common move. White defends their d5-pawn rather than trading on e6. If given the chance, White will play the move e4 next to further defend their d5-pawn. We cannot allow this!} 
6. exd5 {We trade on d5 immediately so that White cannot reinforce the pawn with e4.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Nxa6 {The most common move, and I offer this as an interesting alternative. The positions that arise after this move are a bit different from the main recommendation of7...Be7and having both options available on move seven will force your opponents to be prepared for either choice.The idea with ...Nxa6 is to trade on d5 soon followed by ...Nc7 and then a potential ...d5 advance. The upside of this compared to 7...Be7 is that we will be able to get in the move ...d5 quicker a lot of the time. The downside is that our knight on c7 may be a bit misplaced in the long-term.} 
8. Nxf6+ {Trading knights doesn't bother us.} 
8. Qxf6
9. Nf3
9. Nb4 {We improve our knight and prepare to play ...Qg6 or ...Qf5 to aim towards the c2-square.} 
10. a3 {I could easily see someone making this blunder.} 
10. Qf5 {A unique way to aim towards the c2-square but now White cannot stop ...Nc2+ in a comfortable way.10...Qg6?This square is not as good since White can play Ne5-d3 now.11.Ne5Qf512.Nd3White has stopped our ...Nc2+ threat.} 
11. g4
11. Qe4 {Not getting distracted from our goal of ...Nc2+. White's knight on f3 is pinned to the rook on h1 now too. White is in huge trouble.} 
