6. exd5 {We trade on d5 immediately so that White cannot reinforce the pawn with e4.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Nxa6 {The most common move, and I offer this as an interesting alternative. The positions that arise after this move are a bit different from the main recommendation of7...Be7and having both options available on move seven will force your opponents to be prepared for either choice.The idea with ...Nxa6 is to trade on d5 soon followed by ...Nc7 and then a potential ...d5 advance. The upside of this compared to 7...Be7 is that we will be able to get in the move ...d5 quicker a lot of the time. The downside is that our knight on c7 may be a bit misplaced in the long-term.} 
8. Bg5 {White's most popular response is to pin our knight and prevent the trade on d5.} 
8. Be7 {We break the pin and threaten to capture on d5.} 
9. Nxe7
9. Qxe7 {Now we want to play ...Qe5 next to attack both the bishop and b2-pawn if possible.} 
10. e3 {White prepares to develop their light-square bishop but doesn't defend against our ...Qe5 idea.} 
10. Qe5
11. Nf3
11. Qxb2 {Being greedy for the b2-pawn looks risky but is perfectly fine to play.} 
12. Bc4
12. Qc3+ {Forking the king and bishop on c4 forces white's response.} 
13. Nd2
13. Ne4 {We double attack the bishop and threaten ...Nxd2 followed by ...Qxa1.} 
14. Bd5 {White has to counterattack with this move.} 
14. Nxd2
15. Rc1 {White's only move is to counterattack our queen on c3.15.Bxa8??Capturing our a8-rook loses the game immediately for White.15...Nf3+16.Ke2Nxg5-+We have two pieces for the rook and have a winning advantage.} 
15. Qb4
16. Qxd2 {Now capturing the knight is safe since there is no hanging rook on a1.} 
16. Ra7
17. Rc4 {White threatens our queen as well as Re4+.} 
17. Qxd2+
18. Kxd2
18. f6 {We need to play this in order to free up the d8-square for our king in case of Re4+.} 
19. Bf4
19. Bb7 {And now we trade off the light-square bishops.} 
20. Bxb7
20. Rxb7 {The position is balanced with us having a passed c-pawn and White having a passed a-pawn. I would say that our position is slightly easier to play since white's a-pawn is weaker than our c-pawn. We can play ...Ke7, ...d6 and double rooks on the b-file to have good play. Playing ...d5 and ...c4 followed by ...Nc5-d3 is also possible.} 
