7. a5 {Continuing forward anyway and harassing the queen.7.Nc3Trying to go back into the regular lines withNc3doesn't help. The damage has already been done by pushing the pawn to a4.7...exd58.Nxd5Nxd59.Qxd5Nc6-+White's a4 move has not only wasted time but also weakened the b4-square and b2-pawn significantly.  You may wonder, 'Why does a4 weaken the b2-pawn?' This is because White can no longer play b3 to keep the pawn safe since there isn't a pawn on a2 anymore.  This means that a lot of the set-ups that White may try to play from here will be hard to accomplish since the b-pawn will be a constant concern. With that in mind, Black already has a terrific position and can develop, followed by attacking the queenside quickly.7.dxe6Similar to trying to play Nc3 now, trading pawns on e6 doesn't fix things since the damage has already been done by playing a4.7...fxe6∓The a4-pawn sticks out like a sore thumb and weakens the b4-square and makes the b2-pawn harder to defend.} 
7. Qd6 {We attack the d5-pawn again and semi-pin the pawn at the same time.} 
8. dxe6
8. Qxd1+
9. Kxd1
9. fxe6 {We already have a crushing position. Material is equal, white's king is stuck in the center, the a5-pawn needs constant protection and white's position is a train wreck.} 
