8. Nc6 {Blocking the queen from attacking our a8-rook. These last few moves are pretty much forced but here White has a few different directions they can go. The typical set-up for White is to play e4 or Nf3 (in some order) followed by Bc4, O-O and then developing the dark-square bishop. Be careful though! The move order that White plays is very important to be aware of.} 
9. Bf4 {White has played this move a bit in the u2000 lichess database. The idea may be to play Bc7 next and keep the b-pawn safe. However, the downside to this move is that the b2-pawn is now undefended and we can target it quickly.} 
9. Qxb6 {Recapturing the pawn now since we threaten b2 along the way.9...Be7??Don't blunder your queen here!10.Bc7+-} 
10. O-O-O {White defends their b2-pawn with the king but will come under a swift attack soon. The king cannot be safe on the queenside with a half-open b-file.} 
10. d6 {Blocking off the bishop from controlling the b8-square and looking to play ...Rb8 and ...Be6 soon.} 
11. Bxd6 {Taking the pawn gets White into huge trouble. They cannot be greedy for material when their king is so weak.} 
11. Bxd6
12. Qxd6
12. Be6 {We are down a pawn (what's new?) but have an incredibly strong attack coming against white's queenside. Next, we will play ...Rd8 to kick white's queen followed by kingside castling. White's kingside pieces are all sleeping on their starting squares and will not be able to come to the king's rescue quickly enough. The a2 and b2-pawns will get captured in the near future.} 
