5. e3 {The 'Modern' variation is one of the best options for White to play if they are not going to fully accept our Benko Gambit. I have played this option in many games as White myself. This calm-looking move simply defends the b5-pawn with the bishop and waits for Black to make a decision about what they're going to do.The most popular options here are to play5...g6or5...axb5. However, I am going to recommend a more rare option5...e6which fits in perfectly with our mainline of the Benko Gambit Fully Accepted.} 
5. e6 {We want to break down white's space advantage in the center as quickly as possible, just like in the mainline. White only has two move options here that make any sense:6.Nc3defending the pawn and6.dxe6trading pawns. If White decides to play the Modern variation then they will most likely play6.Nc3since the other option of6.dxe6is much more rare.That being said, trading pawns on e6 is probably the slightly better of the two options! So it's good news for us that it is much less likely to happen in a practical game. I will still give a good explanation about what to do against dxe6 too of course.} 
6. Nc3 {I am labeling this as the mainline since it is a much more popular response. White defends their d5-pawn similar to the Nc3 move in the mainline of the Benko Gambit Fully Accepted.6.bxa6?If White is going to capture a pawn then it is too late to take on a6.6...Nxd5⩱Next we will capture on a6 (probably with the bishop) and enjoy a space superiority in the center of the board.6.d6?Pushing up to d6 cramps us for a moment but the pawn is overextended and will be captured soon.6...Ne4⩱We take d6 next move with a good position. Make sure you capture with the knight so that White doesn't have tactics involving kicking our knight off the e4-square and winning our bishop on d6! If White plays Qf3 to pin the knight then we can simply play ...Bb7 to break the pin.} 
6. exd5 {Just like in the mainline, we trade pawns on d5 immediately and get rid of white's space advantage before White can play e4 to solidify their d5-pawn more.} 
7. Nxd5
7. Bb7 {Now we attack white's loose knight. We need to put some pressure on the center of the board so that White doesn't get to play e4 easily.} 
8. Nxf6+
8. Qxf6 {Now White has to be careful about the bishop on f1 being overworked defending the b5 and g2-pawns.} 
9. Nf3 {Developing a piece and blocking off our b7-bishop is white's most popular move.} 
9. Be7 {We develop and prepare to castle.} 
10. bxa6 {White trades on a6 so that they don't burn time by moving the bishop from f1, then having to capture on b5 afterwards anyways.} 
10. Bxa6 {Our main option is going to be capturing with the bishop on a6 to fight for control of the f1-a6 diagonal and try to make it difficult for White to castle kingside. An alternative option is also given in this chapter which is ...Nxa6 here.} 
11. Bxa6
11. Qxa6 {We now have good control over the f1-a6 diagonal which means White will not be able to castle easily. Our next moves are ...O-O and ...Bf6 to pressure the queenside pawns.} 
12. Qe2 {White offers a queen trade in order to fix their king safety issue.12.Bd2Bf6You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games HERE.} 
12. Bf6 {We don't want to trade on e2 since that would allow White to play Rd1 and get their rook in the game quickly. Also, the king would be well-placed on the e2-square. Rather, we wait for White to take our queen on a6 instead so that we accelerate our own development.} 
13. a3 {White stares us down and waits for us to flinch. But we are not going to trade on e2 and help them out!} 
13. Nc6 {We develop our knight instead. We will play ...d5, ...Kd7 or ...Ke7, ...Rhb8 and pressure the queenside pawns. Playing ...Nb4-d3 may also be an idea in some situations. We have good compensation for the pawn due to active pieces and queenside pressure.} 
