*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Benko Gambit Half-Accepted 5.Nc3 Zaitsev"]
[Black "5.Nc3 axb5 6.Nxb5 e6 7.Nc3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. Nc3 {This move characterizes the Zaitsev variation against the Benko Gambit. This variation allows Black to regain their gambited pawn but does have some bit behind it. The purpose of 5. Nc3 is to play a quick e4 in the center and follow this up with e5 in the near future.   White tries to take advantage of a slight lead in development that they will have and wants to blast the center of the board open quickly in order to do that. Black has plenty of answers to this variation, though and it is not very popular nowadays. A 55.2% score for Black from this position shows that Black is happy to see this variation in practice.} 
5. axb5 {We should capture on b5. If White doesn't take the pawn then we will play ...b4 and if they do capture on b5 against then we'll play in our computerized Benko-style with ...e6!?} 
6. Nxb5 {This recapture is relatively rare at the master level, considering White will usually capture on a6 if they wanted to hold onto the extra pawn.On the other hand, this response is very common in the u2000 lichess database with 5 times as many games being played this way compared to6.e4. The downside to recapturing on b5 now is that the knight will most likely need to move another time in the near future.  That being said, this move altered the trajectory of the game a bit and forces us to change our set-up.} 
6. e6 {I like the idea of harassing white's d5-pawn and looking to get a space advantage in the center. White really only has one critical option here.} 
7. Nc3 {Moving back to defend the pawn costs White a lot of time. The principle of 'don't move the same piece more than once in the opening' is generally good for a reason!} 
7. exd5
8. Nxd5
8. Bb7
9. e4 {If White is going to go for this variation then playing e4 here is the trickiest attempt for them. White gives back a pawn in order to keep their knight on the d5-square but we're happy to equalize material ourselves.} 
9. Nxe4 {Playing ...Qa5+ is most likely our next move.} 
10. Bc4
10. Qa5+
11. Kf1 {White is forced to move the king to avoid an even worse position. Now we need to be careful about Bf4 and Qe2 moves with quick threats against our centralized king.} 
11. Nc6
12. Bf4
12. Nd6 {Retreating the knight to a safer square and blocking off white's f4-bishop.} 
13. Qe2+
13. Kd8 {It's not everyday you get an opening variation where both sides have moved their king and not castled! Here we are objectively better though since our king is surprisingly safer. We threaten ideas of ...Nd4 and sometimes ...Nxc4 followed by ...Ba6.} 
