2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. Nc3 {This move characterizes the Zaitsev variation against the Benko Gambit. This variation allows Black to regain their gambited pawn but does have some bit behind it. The purpose of 5. Nc3 is to play a quick e4 in the center and follow this up with e5 in the near future.   White tries to take advantage of a slight lead in development that they will have and wants to blast the center of the board open quickly in order to do that. Black has plenty of answers to this variation, though and it is not very popular nowadays. A 55.2% score for Black from this position shows that Black is happy to see this variation in practice.} 
5. axb5 {We should capture on b5. If White doesn't take the pawn then we will play ...b4 and if they do capture on b5 against then we'll play in our computerized Benko-style with ...e6!?} 
6. e4 {White's most popular move and the one that goes along with the plan mentioned earlier (e4-e5).   Objectively, White should probably be capturing the pawn on b5 which we'll look at in other variations but you will see that move a lot less often since if White wanted to keep the extra pawn, they usually capture on a6 instead of playing 5. Nc3. With 6. e4, White is looking to play e5 quickly as well as threatening Bxb5. Our next move is forced.} 
6. b4 {We need to save our b-pawn while creating a threat on white's knight.} 
7. Nb5 {White advances their knight to a very active location. Usually a knight on b5 would be kicked around with the a- or c-pawn but here attacking the knight is a bit easier said than done. We will see plenty of variations where we harass this knight but it will be done later on with pieces rather than pawns. Now we need to deal with white's e5 threat.7.e5?Pushing to e5 too quickly is a big mistake here and in many other variations White has to be careful about playing e5 at the wrong time too. We can punish this quickly.7...bxc38.exf6cxb29.Bxb2Qa5+!An important move to insert. White has to play Qd2 which allows a queen trade after which we will be ahead a pawn.10.Qd2Qxd2+11.Kxd2gxf6-+Capturing towards the center on f6 is important.  We'll see this capture in many variations against the Trompowsky opening too. Here Black is simply ahead a pawn and White has isolated pawns on a2 and d5 which we can target. Black is much better.} 
7. d6 {We control the e5-square and prevent White from advancing their pawn. Here we have a fork in the road and there are many different move options that White has available now. We'll examine most of them here.7...Nxe4??We will see this capture in a few variations but only when it is safe to go for. Here is it way too greedy and we will lose the game very quickly.8.Qe2If we retreat our knight then Nd6 is checkmate! This has actually happened 226 times in the u2000 lichess database. You will not be number 227 as long as you study this chapter :-)8...f59.f3+-Our knight is lost due to the Nd6+ follow-up if we move.} 
8. Bc4 {White develops their light-square bishop and points in the direction of the f7-pawn. The typical idea behind this move is to play a two-pawn sacrifice next with e5 dxe5, d6 exd6, Bg5. Fortunately for us, this popular variation is much better for Black!} 
8. Nbd7 {If you want to avoid the main variations and not let White play e5 then this is the way to go.} 
9. Nf3
9. Nb6
10. b3 {Not a very popular move but objectively it is white's best way to respond to our threat on their bishop.10.Bd3White wastes too much time moving the bishop again.10...g611.b3Bg712.Bb2O-O13.O-OBa6The position is balanced but I tend to prefer Black because white's knight is stranded and if White plays a4 or a3 then we can trade pawns and give White an isolated b3-pawn which is a nice target to attack later.} 
10. Nxe4
11. O-O
11. Nxc4
12. bxc4
12. Nc3 {It is important to get the knight out of the line of fire and trade off white's b5-knight which is tying us down to the defense of the d6-pawn.} 
13. Nxc3
13. bxc3
14. Re1 {14.Qd3You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games HERE.} 
14. h6 {Keeping pieces off the g5-square.} 
15. Qd3
15. e5
16. dxe6 {If White doesn't capture en passant then we will be ahead a pawn with zero trouble in the center and with the bishop pair.} 
16. Bxe6
17. Qxc3
17. Be7
18. Qxg7 {White has to try taking g7 and invest material to keep some pressure on our king.} 
18. Bf6
19. Rxe6+
19. fxe6
20. Qg6+
20. Ke7
21. Rb1
21. Rb8
22. Rxb8
22. Qxb8 {The computer calls this an equal position but I find it very hard to believe that White can hold this in a game between two humans. The queenside pawns are weak and Black is ahead an exchange. Maybe White can draw but I can't forsee any way that Black is ever in any trouble here.} 
