7. Nb5 {White advances their knight to a very active location. Usually a knight on b5 would be kicked around with the a- or c-pawn but here attacking the knight is a bit easier said than done. We will see plenty of variations where we harass this knight but it will be done later on with pieces rather than pawns. Now we need to deal with white's e5 threat.7.e5?Pushing to e5 too quickly is a big mistake here and in many other variations White has to be careful about playing e5 at the wrong time too. We can punish this quickly.7...bxc38.exf6cxb29.Bxb2Qa5+!An important move to insert. White has to play Qd2 which allows a queen trade after which we will be ahead a pawn.10.Qd2Qxd2+11.Kxd2gxf6-+Capturing towards the center on f6 is important.  We'll see this capture in many variations against the Trompowsky opening too. Here Black is simply ahead a pawn and White has isolated pawns on a2 and d5 which we can target. Black is much better.} 
7. d6 {We control the e5-square and prevent White from advancing their pawn. Here we have a fork in the road and there are many different move options that White has available now. We'll examine most of them here.7...Nxe4??We will see this capture in a few variations but only when it is safe to go for. Here is it way too greedy and we will lose the game very quickly.8.Qe2If we retreat our knight then Nd6 is checkmate! This has actually happened 226 times in the u2000 lichess database. You will not be number 227 as long as you study this chapter :-)8...f59.f3+-Our knight is lost due to the Nd6+ follow-up if we move.} 
8. Bc4 {White develops their light-square bishop and points in the direction of the f7-pawn. The typical idea behind this move is to play a two-pawn sacrifice next with e5 dxe5, d6 exd6, Bg5. Fortunately for us, this popular variation is much better for Black!} 
8. g6 {The second most popular option for Black but it follows our principle on move 8 and it is objectively the best move while also inviting White to go for a variation that is favorable for us. Let's examine white's popular sacrificial continuation.} 
9. e5 {White sacrifices the first pawn to open up the center of the board.9.Nf3If White doesn't sacrifice with e5 immediately, then we can simply continue our development.9...Bg710.O-OO-OCapturing on e4 has been possible but I think we can avoid the complications and still have the advantage.  I am mainly recommending capturing the e4 pawn only when it is the only good option for us, but otherwise avoiding the ensuing counterplay that White usually gets.11.Re1Bg4⩱We will trade our bishop on f3 for the knight, play ...Nbd7-e5 or b6 and look to target white's b5-knight or a2-pawn.} 
9. dxe5
10. Nf3 {White should seek to win their e5-pawn back instead of giving up a second pawn. However, you are very unlikely to see this move since the whole point of White playing 9. e5 is to play 10. d6.} 
10. Bg7 {We focus on development rather than holding onto the e5-pawn.} 
11. Nxe5
11. O-O
12. O-O
12. Ne4 {I like maneuvering the knight towards the d6-square in order to blockade white's d5-pawn and prevent it from advancing easily. White's knight on e5 is also being attacked right now. The position is dynamically balanced with white's pieces being a bit more active but they do have a pawn weakness on d5 in the long-term.} 
