[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Benko Gambit Half-Accepted 5.Nc3 Zaitsev"]
[Black "5.Nc3 axb5 6.e4 b4 7.Nb5 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5
4. a6
5. Nc3 {This move characterizes the Zaitsev variation against the Benko Gambit. This variation allows Black to regain their gambited pawn but does have some bit behind it. The purpose of 5. Nc3 is to play a quick e4 in the center and follow this up with e5 in the near future.   White tries to take advantage of a slight lead in development that they will have and wants to blast the center of the board open quickly in order to do that. Black has plenty of answers to this variation, though and it is not very popular nowadays. A 55.2% score for Black from this position shows that Black is happy to see this variation in practice.} 
5. axb5 {We should capture on b5. If White doesn't take the pawn then we will play ...b4 and if they do capture on b5 against then we'll play in our computerized Benko-style with ...e6!?} 
6. e4 {White's most popular move and the one that goes along with the plan mentioned earlier (e4-e5).   Objectively, White should probably be capturing the pawn on b5 which we'll look at in other variations but you will see that move a lot less often since if White wanted to keep the extra pawn, they usually capture on a6 instead of playing 5. Nc3. With 6. e4, White is looking to play e5 quickly as well as threatening Bxb5. Our next move is forced.} 
6. b4 {We need to save our b-pawn while creating a threat on white's knight.} 
7. Nb5 {White advances their knight to a very active location. Usually a knight on b5 would be kicked around with the a- or c-pawn but here attacking the knight is a bit easier said than done. We will see plenty of variations where we harass this knight but it will be done later on with pieces rather than pawns. Now we need to deal with white's e5 threat.7.e5?Pushing to e5 too quickly is a big mistake here and in many other variations White has to be careful about playing e5 at the wrong time too. We can punish this quickly.7...bxc38.exf6cxb29.Bxb2Qa5+!An important move to insert. White has to play Qd2 which allows a queen trade after which we will be ahead a pawn.10.Qd2Qxd2+11.Kxd2gxf6-+Capturing towards the center on f6 is important.  We'll see this capture in many variations against the Trompowsky opening too. Here Black is simply ahead a pawn and White has isolated pawns on a2 and d5 which we can target. Black is much better.} 
7. d6 {We control the e5-square and prevent White from advancing their pawn. Here we have a fork in the road and there are many different move options that White has available now. We'll examine most of them here.7...Nxe4??We will see this capture in a few variations but only when it is safe to go for. Here is it way too greedy and we will lose the game very quickly.8.Qe2If we retreat our knight then Nd6 is checkmate! This has actually happened 226 times in the u2000 lichess database. You will not be number 227 as long as you study this chapter :-)8...f59.f3+-Our knight is lost due to the Nd6+ follow-up if we move.} 
8. Bc4 {White develops their light-square bishop and points in the direction of the f7-pawn. The typical idea behind this move is to play a two-pawn sacrifice next with e5 dxe5, d6 exd6, Bg5. Fortunately for us, this popular variation is much better for Black!} 
8. g6 {The second most popular option for Black but it follows our principle on move 8 and it is objectively the best move while also inviting White to go for a variation that is favorable for us. Let's examine white's popular sacrificial continuation.} 
9. e5 {White sacrifices the first pawn to open up the center of the board.9.Nf3If White doesn't sacrifice with e5 immediately, then we can simply continue our development.9...Bg710.O-OO-OCapturing on e4 has been possible but I think we can avoid the complications and still have the advantage.  I am mainly recommending capturing the e4 pawn only when it is the only good option for us, but otherwise avoiding the ensuing counterplay that White usually gets.11.Re1Bg4⩱We will trade our bishop on f3 for the knight, play ...Nbd7-e5 or b6 and look to target white's b5-knight or a2-pawn.} 
9. dxe5
10. d6 {This second pawn sacrifice is exclusively played in every game in the database but it gives us the advantage as long as we know the following sequence!} 
10. exd6
11. Bg5 {White pins our knight and creates a lot of threats, one of which is Bxf6 followed by Nc7+. The following move for us is very important to memorize.} 
11. Nbd7 {The only move for Black that gives us an advantage but it does the job! This has only been played a handful of times compared to everything else having been played many more times. It looks very counter-intuitive to play this since it blocks off the defense of the d6-pawn but we are willing to give back at least one pawn in order to create counterplay, activate our pieces and turn the initiative in our favor.} 
12. Qb3 {White targets the f7-pawn. We are not able to defend this pawn but we are willing to give back at least one pawn to turn the initiative in our favor.} 
12. Qa5 {We get out of the pin, open up the d8-square for our king and put some pressure on white's b5-knight.} 
13. Bxf7+
13. Kd8
14. Bc4
14. Ba6 {White's b5-knight is trapped and hard to constantly defend.} 
15. Qf3 {White should try counterattacking our pinned f6-knight. This will not equalize for them though.} 
15. Bxb5
16. Bxb5 {16.Bxf6+??White may think they're winning material, but it ends up that their own king will come under a vicious attack.16...Kc7!17.Bxh8(17.Bxb5b3+!Transposes to the main variation).17...b3+!18.Kd1Bh6Threatening mate on d2.19.Qc3Qxc320.bxc3Bxc4-+We are down the exchange, but the b-pawn will win us the game soon.} 
16. Kc7 {We get out of the pin and threaten to play ...e4 to block off white's queen's diagonal towards our a8-rook and then capture white's bishop on b5.} 
17. Bxd7 {This gets rid of white's loose bishop but trading pieces only helps us since we're still ahead a pawn.} 
17. Nxd7
18. Ne2
18. Bg7
19. O-O
19. e4 {Opening up the diagonal towards the b2-pawn and harassing the queen.} 
20. Qxe4
20. Rhe8
21. Qf3
21. Bxb2 {After white's rook moves away from a1 then we can capture the pawn on a2. At that point we will be ahead two pawns and have a huge mass of queenside pawns that can eventually move down the board to promote. Black is completely winning.} 
