8. Bf4 {White's most popular move but fortunately for us, this already gives us an objective advantage!} 
8. Nbd7 {It's always nice when a simple move gives us an advantage compared to needing to memorize captures that lead to a complicated position. The principle I like to follow for this chapter is if white's 8th move threatens to play e5 then we play ...Nbd7 to stop it while if their 8th move doesn't threaten ...e5 then we can play ...g6 to accelerate our kingside development.8...g5This is black's best move objectively but not by much. Playing ...g5 here leads to a lot of complications due to our unsafe king and the center of the board opening up very quickly. If you want to look into this move more yourself I would recommend it since the positions are interesting but I like a safer, calmer move when it also still gives us an advantage anyways without needing to enter murky waters unnecessarily.} 
9. Bd3 {White defends their e4-pawn but the combination of Bf4 and Bd3 doesn't make a ton of sense to me. The bishop on f4 will get harassed by ...Nh5 in the future and if White isn't going full-force for e5 then putting the bishop on f4 doesn't seem to be a great location for it. Playing Bd3 also blocks off white's queen from defending the d5-pawn so them playing e5 is less of a threat because we can respond with ...Nxd5.} 
9. g6
10. Nf3
10. Bg7
11. O-O
11. Nh5 {White already faces awkward problems. The bishop and b2-pawn are both attacked.} 
12. Bg5 {White may try to make a threat of Nxd6 due to the e7-pawn being pinned.} 
12. O-O {We can afford to ignore the threat since it is not a real issue for us!} 
13. Qc2 {13.Nxd6??This doesn't work for White.13...f6!The pin is broken and both minor pieces are hanging.14.Nxc8fxg5Capture the bishop first since the knight on c8 is trapped anyways.15.Nxg5Qxc8-+We are ahead a piece.} 
13. Nb6 {Black has an easier position to play. The bishop on g5 is slightly misplaced and will be harassed by ...h6 soon, the pawn on b2 is pinned and needs defense and the knight on b5 is stranded. The typical plan now is to go after the b5-knight and try to win it with ...Ra5 and ...Ba6 or ...Bd7.} 
