21. Qb7 {Next we can play ...Ne7 to trade off white's strong d5-knight.   One important thing about this position to understand is that white's other knight can actually never get to the d5-square since the c3 and e3 squares are protected. This means that after we trade the knights then we can keep the d6-pawn defended and work towards attacking white's a2-pawn which is a weakness in their position.   We may also be able to play ...c4-c3 at some point to create a passed pawn for ourselves. The computer says this position is equal though but I would argue that while White has better short-term chances, I think we have the better long-term position due to white's pawn on a2 being weaker than our d6-pawn and the ability to create a passed pawn easier.} 
