1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Nf3 {The most popular way to decline the Benko Gambit. White decides to not capture on b5 and instead waits for us to make a decision regarding our b-pawn.   The drawback to this move is that it blocks the f-pawn and doesn't put any pressure on us and lets us make a free move. For this reason, this chapter we will see more a3 advances from White and in the Qc2 chapter we will see more f4 advances.} 
4. b4 {In this particular variation, we are going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkward for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions! Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6, play ...a5 and push our e-pawn to e6 (to attack white's d5-pawn) or e5 (to close the center).} 
5. Nbd2 {Another very popular way of developing for White. They want to play e4 as soon as they can.} 
5. g6 {We stick to the typical development scheme.} 
6. e4
6. d6
7. Bd3
7. Bg7
8. O-O
8. O-O {White has many moves available from here. Against most of their moves we will play things like ...Nbd7, ...a5, ...Ba6, ...Qc7 and ...Nb6 to aim at the c4-pawn.} 
9. a3
9. a5
10. h3
10. Nbd7 {Transposes to THIS VARIATION.} 
