[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Benko Gambit Declined 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4. Nf3 b4 5.b3 e6 6.Bb2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Nf3 {The most popular way to decline the Benko Gambit. White decides to not capture on b5 and instead waits for us to make a decision regarding our b-pawn.   The drawback to this move is that it blocks the f-pawn and doesn't put any pressure on us and lets us make a free move. For this reason, this chapter we will see more a3 advances from White and in the Qc2 chapter we will see more f4 advances.} 
4. b4 {In this particular variation, we are going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkward for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions! Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6, play ...a5 and push our e-pawn to e6 (to attack white's d5-pawn) or e5 (to close the center).} 
5. b3
5. e6 {White is not ready to play e4 yet and reinforce their d5-pawn. This means that we can strike at the d5-pawn with our ...e6 pawn break.} 
6. Bb2 {Focusing on development.6...exd5?!Trading on d5 actually ends up making it easier for White to defend their d5-pawn due to the half-open e-file towards our king.7.cxd5Bb78.e4±We have to be very careful here and probably don't want to take the e4-pawn since developing the kingside will be difficult after that. White has a great position all of a sudden because of our pawn trade on d5 earlier.} 
6. Bb7 {We don't want to trade on d5 just yet. We would rather wait for White to take us on e6.} 
7. e4 {This is a tricky move to meet if you're caught unaware. White sacrifices a pawn for development.} 
7. Nxe4 {We must accept the sacrifice.} 
8. Bd3
8. Nf6 {The computer recommends playing ...exd5 but this leads to a huge mess with our king being stuck in the center. Retreating to f6 is much, much simpler in comparison. We don't need to greed for a second pawn.} 
9. O-O
9. Be7
10. Re1
10. O-O {White has some compensation for the pawn due to their active pieces but now they need to be careful about their d5-pawn being captured soon. If they trade pawns on e6 then we are very happy about that since our b7-bishop would open up and our knight could develop to c6.} 
11. Qe2 {An annoying move for us. White pins our e6-pawn so that we cannot capture on d5.} 
11. Ne8 {An important move for us. We retreat the knight and plan to put our bishop on f6 to start trading pieces. It is usually good to trade pieces when you're ahead on material and on top of that, it is good to trade pieces when you are being attacked. White's pieces are more active so it is clear that we should be trading!} 
12. Nbd2
12. Bf6
13. Ne4
13. Bxb2
14. Qxb2 {Our c5-pawn is hit.} 
14. Na6
15. Neg5 {Now our h7-pawn.} 
15. Nf6 {White still has some compensation for the pawn but as they start running out of ways to make a threat, they will need to trade pawns on e6 sooner or later. Our extra pawn will matter in the long-run once we weather white's short-term pressure.} 
