[Black "4. Nf3 b4 5.a3 g6 6.axb4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Nf3 {The most popular way to decline the Benko Gambit. White decides to not capture on b5 and instead waits for us to make a decision regarding our b-pawn.   The drawback to this move is that it blocks the f-pawn and doesn't put any pressure on us and lets us make a free move. For this reason, this chapter we will see more a3 advances from White and in the Qc2 chapter we will see more f4 advances.} 
4. b4 {In this particular variation, we are going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkward for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions! Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6, play ...a5 and push our e-pawn to e6 (to attack white's d5-pawn) or e5 (to close the center).} 
5. a3 {The most common response but by a very small margin. White challenges our b4-pawn and hopes that we will capture on a3 so that the c3-square will open up for White's knight. We are pretty much never going to be capturing on a3 and will almost always leave the pawn on b4 and wait for White to make the trade.} 
5. g6 {It's best for us to stick to the usual development scheme here. A lot of the time we will respond to a3 with ...a5 but usually that would be after we have developed the kingside a bit more.} 
6. axb4 {White trades on b4 which releases their c4-pawn to advance forward in the future.} 
6. cxb4 {White may try to use their c-pawn in some cases but we may also be able to use the weak c5-square to maneuver a knight to one day.} 
7. Nbd2 {White can prepare the pawn advance without immediately pushing too.} 
7. Bg7 {Back to the usual development.} 
8. e4
8. d6 {We need to stop the pawn from pushing to e5. This seems like a mistake though due to white's response.} 
9. Qa4+ {Forking the king and undefended b4-pawn.} 
9. Nfd7 {We should block with the f6-knight so that we can gain control of the c5-square as soon as possible. Blocking with the bishop would only put it in the way and using the b8-knight to block wouldn't be as good since that knight should go to the a6-square soon.} 
10. Qxb4
10. a5 {All other games had continued with ...Na6 here but pushing to a5 first seems better since we also gain control over the b4-square.} 
11. Qa4
11. O-O {We're down a pawn but have strong compensation due to our lead in development and great dark-square control with ...Nc5 coming next.} 
12. Nb3 {White prevents ...Nc5 for now but leaves their queen with very few squares.} 
12. Nb6 {Harassing the queen and aiming at the c4-pawn.} 
13. Qa2 {From a2 the queen can help to defend the c4-pawn if necessary.13.Qa3?!This square makes it more difficult for the queen to get back towards the action.13...Ba6!Going after the c4-pawn.  White doesn't have a good way to defend the pawn without making some kind of concession. If they play Nxa5 we can respond with ...Bxc4.  If they put one of the knights on d2 then their dark-square bishop is blocked in and we may continue with ...Qc7 or ...a4 with a good position.} 
13. e6 {Now we break at the center of the board and work to open the e-file toward white's uncastled king. We have strong compensation for the pawn due to our active pieces, good control of the dark-squares and the ability to open the center of the board soon and take advantage of white's weak king.} 
