[Black "4. Qc2 b4 5.b3 g6 6.Bb2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Qc2 {This is the most popular move if White is not wanting to capture the b5-pawn on the fourth move. White decides to develop their queen a bit, defend the c4-pawn and aim to play e4 next move.   Against this move, we will be playing similarly to the 4. Nf3 Benko Gambit Declined variation, and we will see transpositions from time to time as well.} 
4. b4 {In this variation, we are again going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkard for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions!   Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6 and put the knight on d7 along with playing ...a5 at various moments.} 
5. b3 {White develops their bishop to b2 quickly but the queen seems a bit misplaced on c2 if White isn't going for e4 immediately.} 
5. g6 {We'll match the bishop on the long diagonal.} 
6. Bb2
6. Bg7
7. e4
7. d6 {When the pawn advances to e4 then we should usually respond with ...d6 to prevent White from playing e5.} 
8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. Bd3
9. e5 {In a lot of the ...c5, ... b4 pawn structures throughout this course we are playing ...e6 to attack white's center. However, in this situation we can get away with playing ...e5 instead.   What are the differences between ...e6 and ...e5?   One is that the a1-h8 diagonal is blocked with our pawn. This makes our bishop on g7 bad but also gains us some space in the center at the same time.   White's bishop on b2 is also blocked out a bit by this ...e5 pawn. Another thing this pawn advance does is it cuts the board in half. What I mean by this is that now that the center is closed down, the focus of the game will be on the flanks, specifically the kingside since the queenside is also a bit closed down.   On the kingside we can now play for ...Nh5 and ...f5 while ...a5, ...Ra7-f7 is an idea too.} 
10. dxe6 {Trading on e6 only helps us.} 
10. Bxe6
11. O-O
11. Nc6 {White's dark-squares (especially d4) are weak due to their pawns being on the light-squares. Next we can play ...Nd7 to trade off the dark-square bishops and leave White with a bad bishop on d3. Our position is very pleasant.} 
