[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Benko Gambit Declined 4.Qc2"]
[Black "4. Qc2 b4 5.a3 a5 6.axb4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. Qc2 {This is the most popular move if White is not wanting to capture the b5-pawn on the fourth move. White decides to develop their queen a bit, defend the c4-pawn and aim to play e4 next move.   Against this move, we will be playing similarly to the 4. Nf3 Benko Gambit Declined variation, and we will see transpositions from time to time as well.} 
4. b4 {In this variation, we are again going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkard for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions!   Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6 and put the knight on d7 along with playing ...a5 at various moments.} 
5. a3 {White challenges our ...b4 pawn immediately.} 
5. a5 {Pretty much everytime White plays a3, we will respond with ...a5 to add extra defense to the pawn.} 
6. axb4
6. cxb4 {One nice thing about this trade of pawns is that it opens up the c5-square that we may be able to maneuver a knight to in the future.} 
7. Nf3
7. g6 {Before maneuvering the knight to c5 we should prioritize our kingside development first though.} 
8. e4
8. d6
9. Be2 {White avoids Bd3 since it will only be a target from a knight on c5.} 
9. Bg7
10. O-O
10. O-O
11. Be3
11. Na6 {We now maneuver towards the c5-square.} 
12. Nd4 {White aims for the c6-square in response.} 
12. Bd7 {Keeping an eye on the c6-square.} 
13. Nd2
13. Qc7 {I like our position. Despite having less central space, we have more space on the queenside, a potential passed a-pawn (after a future ...a4-a3), a good c5-square for a knight and pressure against white's e4 and c4-pawns.} 
