3. d5
3. b5
4. Qc2 {This is the most popular move if White is not wanting to capture the b5-pawn on the fourth move. White decides to develop their queen a bit, defend the c4-pawn and aim to play e4 next move.   Against this move, we will be playing similarly to the 4. Nf3 Benko Gambit Declined variation, and we will see transpositions from time to time as well.} 
4. b4 {In this variation, we are again going to use our free move to gain more space on the queenside and make it awkard for White to develop their b1-knight to the active c3-square.   This way of playing tends to take the game a bit away from the usual active piece play and open queenside types of positions we will usually get in the Benko Gambit but we will still be able to have enjoyable positions!   Our general plan in this structure is to develop our bishop to g7, play ...d6 and put the knight on d7 along with playing ...a5 at various moments.} 
5. e4 {White's most popular move. They want to play e5 next.} 
5. d6 {We cannot afford to let the pawn to push to e5 too quickly. Now White has a lot of move options but we will respond to many of them with the same set-ups.} 
6. f4 {White may charge forward with their f-pawn before playing Nf3 but this doesn't alter our original set-up just yet.} 
6. g6
7. e5 {White continues the avalanche of pawns in the center. This requires a bit of precision to respond to but if we know what we're doing then Black is perfectly fine here.} 
7. dxe5
8. fxe5
8. Ng4 {We attack the pawn from g4 so that we keep the d7-square open for our other pieces.} 
9. Nf3
9. Bg7
10. Bf4
10. Nd7 {Continuing to aim directly at the e5-pawn with the goal of proving that it is overextended and weak.} 
11. Qe2 {Defending the pawn from e2 with the queen allows an interesting option.} 
11. e6 {We prevent White from playing e6 themselves and lock the e5-pawn in place so that we can attack it more as the game goes on.} 
12. h3 {A reasonable looking move that ends up being a mistake due to the following sacrifice.} 
12. Ngxe5 {We sacrifice the knight for a pawn but open up the diagonal for our g7-bishop which will be very useful in the next sequence of moves.} 
13. Nxe5
13. Qf6 {Both of white's pieces in the center are hit and the knight is also pinned to the b2-pawn.} 
14. Nd3 {It seems like White has solved all their problems.} 
14. O-O {Despite being down a piece for a pawn, white's development is very bad due to the bishop on f1 being blocked, their king being stuck in the center and we are about to blast open the center once our e-pawn gets moving.} 
15. dxe6 {White tries to keep the e-file closed, hoping that we will play ...fxe6 here.} 
15. Re8 {We have no intention of closing the e-file down and will instead take back with the rook on e6 to open the file.} 
16. Kd1
16. Rxe6
17. Qf3
17. Nb6 {Defending our a8-rook and preparing to develop our light-square bishop.} 
18. Nd2
18. Bd7 {We have a lot of compensation for the piece here. White has to worry about moves such as ...Ba4+ followed by ...Rd8 or ...Rae8 with more pressure down the center of the board. Practically speaking, White is in a ton of trouble here and could quickly lose if they aren't very careful.} 
