6. Nf3 {White calmly develops their kingside knight.6.Nd2g6You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games HERE.} 
6. g6
7. Bd3
7. Bg7
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. h3 {White keeps any of our pieces off the g4-square and may develop the bishop to f4 and keep the h2-square open for it to retreat to later.} 
9. a5 {A bit of a waiting move but also a generally useful move in a lot of situations.} 
10. Bf4 {White develops to f4 but will still get kicked around by our knight and e-pawn.} 
10. Nh5
11. Bh2
11. e5 {Shutting the h2-bishop's diagonal. We will prepare ...f5 and may also play ...Nf4 at some point too.} 
12. Nbd2 {If White doesn't trade pawns in the center then we can continue to build our advantage.} 
12. a4 {Gaining more space before continuing on the kingside.} 
13. Rfe1
13. Nd7 {Making small improvements before pushing forward. White can only sit and watch since they have no active counterplay.} 
14. Rad1
14. Nf4 {White will have a hard time dealing with this knight since playing g3 at any point will not only leave the pawn on h3 undefended but also shut in the bishop on h2. Also, if White trades on f4 then our b7-bishop becomes a monster.} 
15. Bf1
15. Bh6 {More small progress. We will eventually play ...f5 but only after maximum improvement which includes the moves ...Ra7 and ...Kh8.   The f5-pawn break will come with a big effect of opening the f-file and we have a very nice advantage here due to our active plan while White is much more passive instead.} 
