10. Bf4 {White develops to f4 but will still get kicked around by our knight and e-pawn.} 
10. Nh5
11. Bh2
11. e5 {Shutting the h2-bishop's diagonal. We will prepare ...f5 and may also play ...Nf4 at some point too.} 
12. dxe6 {White improves their h2-bishop but also opens our g7-bishop back up along with weakening their dark-squares in the center.} 
12. Bxe6
13. Nbd2
13. Nc6 {Our position is very nice. We have active pieces and can look to play an interesting idea of ...Be5 in order to fight for control of the f4-square. Playing ...a4-a3 is also possible. White's pieces are a bit less active in comparison, especially their queenside pieces.} 
