[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5 {Now we enter the Benko Gambit Declined fourth move sidelines chapter. This chapter will cover all of white's fourth moves that are not4.Nf3,4.Qc2or4.cxb5.  The good news for us is that as is the case with most of the course, there are very few critical lines that will cause us trouble in the sidelines areas. I will note for this chapter that there are many times where we will be transposing into the4.Nf3or4.Qc2chapters because we will be playing ...b4 against a lot of the fourth move options White can throw at us. Not all of them though!} 
4. a4 {With this move White wants us to commit our b-pawn and ideally force us to capture on c4. We will not be going along with white's plan though!} 
4. Qa5+ {We would usually play ...b4 here immediately but I like inserting this queen check in order to disrupt white's coordination.} 
5. Bd2 {White blocks the check with tempo but the bishop also blocks white's knight from developing to d2.} 
5. b4 {The bishop is misplaced and blocks in white's b1-knight. We are never concerned about White playing Na3 using the pin on the b-pawn since we can retreat the queen and force the knight to continue moving to non-useful squares.} 
6. Qc2
6. g6 {Going for the usual development scheme.} 
7. e4
7. d6
8. Bd3
8. Bg7
9. f4
9. O-O {We are not worried about e5 from White since we can trade pawns and play ...Ng4 after which the e-pawn will be lost.} 
10. Nf3
10. e6 {We challenge white's center and look to open up lines for our pieces.} 
11. O-O {11.dxe6?!Bxe6∓You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games HERE.} 
11. exd5
12. cxd5 {This capture gets White into big trouble due to the following forcing move sequence.} 
12. c4 {We temporarily sacrifice a pawn in order to open up the c-file and g1-a7 diagonal.} 
13. Bxc4 {White captures with the bishop so that the queen doesn't get harassed but we can create a pin along the c-file with our next move.} 
13. Qc5+
14. Kh1
14. Ba6 {White's bishop is pinned, and defending it isn't simple.} 
15. b3 {Playing Rc1 would run into ...Ng4 problems.} 
15. Bxc4
16. bxc4
16. Nxe4 {We equalize material and create the threats of ...Nf2+ and ...Bxa1. White cannot stop both threats, and we are winning more material here.} 
