9. O-O {We are not worried about e5 from White since we can trade pawns and play ...Ng4 after which the e-pawn will be lost.} 
10. Nf3
10. e6 {We challenge white's center and look to open up lines for our pieces.} 
11. O-O {11.dxe6?!Bxe6∓You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games HERE.} 
11. exd5
12. exd5 {White must capture this way since the alternative option leads to a really bad position for them.} 
12. Qd8 {The position is balanced but I like our chances. White's queenside pieces are awkwardly placed and we can play ...Re8, ...Nbd7 and ...Ng4 in the near future. White's dark-squares in the center are a bit under-defended.} 
