[White "9) Benko Gambit Declined Fourth Move Sidelines"]
[Black "4.Nc3 b4 5.Nb1 e6 6.g3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5 {Now we enter the Benko Gambit Declined fourth move sidelines chapter. This chapter will cover all of white's fourth moves that are not4.Nf3,4.Qc2or4.cxb5.  The good news for us is that as is the case with most of the course, there are very few critical lines that will cause us trouble in the sidelines areas. I will note for this chapter that there are many times where we will be transposing into the4.Nf3or4.Qc2chapters because we will be playing ...b4 against a lot of the fourth move options White can throw at us. Not all of them though!} 
4. Nc3 {White develops the knight with a 'tempo' on the b5-pawn but walks right into our typical response.} 
4. b4 {The usual pawn advance but this time it also comes with a threat at the same time!} 
5. Nb1 {White puts the knight back on it's starting square but this means that White just burned two moves in the opening which is never a good idea.} 
5. e6 {While there is nothing wrong with playing the usual set-up with ... g6 and ...Bg7 first, I like challenging the center immediately with the typical ...e6 pawn break. This is especially good now since White wasted two moves in the opening. When your opponent plays bad openings moves, opening the center is usually a good response!} 
6. g3 {White prepares to develop the bishop to g2 in order to defend their d5-pawn. If they didn't do this then they would have to be concerned about a quick ...exd5 followed by ...Bb7 when the d5-pawn would be difficult to defend.} 
6. exd5
7. Bg2 {White pins the d5-pawn along the diagonal but will need to capture the pawn on d5 soon anyways.} 
7. g6
8. cxd5
8. Bg7 {We're not concerned about the pawn advancing to d6 since we can respond with ...Nc6. That being said, there was nothing wrong with playing ...d6 before ...Bg7.} 
9. Nf3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. d6 {White is in a rough spot here due to the weakness of the d5-pawn. It is difficult for White to develop their queenside pieces without blocking the queen from defending the pawn. Next, we will play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7-b6 and ...a5 if we need to reinforce our b4-pawn.} 
