[Black "4.Nc3 b4 5.Na4 d6 6.g3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5 {Now we enter the Benko Gambit Declined fourth move sidelines chapter. This chapter will cover all of white's fourth moves that are not4.Nf3,4.Qc2or4.cxb5.  The good news for us is that as is the case with most of the course, there are very few critical lines that will cause us trouble in the sidelines areas. I will note for this chapter that there are many times where we will be transposing into the4.Nf3or4.Qc2chapters because we will be playing ...b4 against a lot of the fourth move options White can throw at us. Not all of them though!} 
4. Nc3 {White develops the knight with a 'tempo' on the b5-pawn but walks right into our typical response.} 
4. b4 {The usual pawn advance but this time it also comes with a threat at the same time!} 
5. Na4 {White moves the knight to the edge of the board but at least they attack our c5-pawn.} 
5. d6 {We defend the pawn and will fianchetto the kingside bishop next.} 
6. g3
6. g6
7. Bg2 {White has a bit of a tricky threat here with Nxc5 followed by d6 attacking our trapped rook on a8.} 
7. a5 {We will usually play this move at some point anyways but it is nice to include it here specifically since it stops white's threat of Nxc5. Now the rook would be able to move off the a8-square if necessary.} 
8. e4
8. Bg7
9. f4
9. Nbd7 {White wanted to play e5 so we stop the advance.} 
10. Qe2 {White continues to prepare the e5 advance.} 
10. O-O {It looks like we allow White to execute their idea...} 
11. e5
11. Re8 {But this move takes the wind out of white's sails! We are willing to sacrifice a piece in order to open up the e-file and create a pin towards white's queen and king. Capturing our knight on f6 will lead to a losing position for White. If they don't take the knight then the pawn on e5 will turn out to be overextended in the near future and we can work towards playing ...e6 ourselves to force the e-file open.} 
12. exf6 {Accepting the piece "sacrifice" will lead to disasater for White.} 
12. exf6
13. Be3
13. f5 {We open up our g7-bishop as well as the f6-square for our knight to move to. Our immediate idea is to play ...Bd4 but ...Nf6-g4 is also a big threat.} 
14. O-O-O {White castles and prepares to play Rd3 to defend the e3-bishop.} 
14. Nf6 {Maneuvering towards the g4-square but also opening up the d7-square so that we can play ...Bd7 and target white's misplaced knight!} 
15. h3 {White stops one threat but not the other idea.} 
15. Bd7
16. b3 {Trying to hold things together but opening up the a1-h8 diagonal towards their king isn't going to end well for White.} 
16. Bxa4
17. bxa4
17. Nh5 {Threatening ...Nxg3 as well as ...Qf6.} 
18. Qf2
18. Qf6 {Sure, White is ahead a piece but look at their useless kingside pieces! White never got to develop them and get them in the game and will instead be mated or lose massive material due to our attack on their king.} 
