3. b5 {Now we enter the Benko Gambit Declined fourth move sidelines chapter. This chapter will cover all of white's fourth moves that are not4.Nf3,4.Qc2or4.cxb5.  The good news for us is that as is the case with most of the course, there are very few critical lines that will cause us trouble in the sidelines areas. I will note for this chapter that there are many times where we will be transposing into the4.Nf3or4.Qc2chapters because we will be playing ...b4 against a lot of the fourth move options White can throw at us. Not all of them though!} 
4. Bg5 {White develops their bishop to g5 sort of like the Trompowsky but not a very good version of it.} 
4. Ne4 {We attack the bishop while also looking to play ...Qa5+ as well.} 
5. Bf4 {The most popular response but we are already better after this move.} 
5. Qa5+
6. Nd2
6. g5 {Gaining a tempo on the bishop while also looking to play ...Bg7 next.} 
7. Be5 {White avoids our threat and makes their own by attacking our rook on h8.} 
7. Rg8 {We move the rook to g8 rather than play ...f6. This is because we want to kick the bishop off e5 next and play ...Bg7 without our bishop being blocked by the f6-pawn.} 
8. Ngf3 {White defends their d2-knight which opens up some b4 Qxb4, Rb1 ideas.} 
8. Nxd2 {Let's trade some pieces so that we can play ...d6 later.} 
