3. d5
3. b5 {Now we enter the Benko Gambit Declined fourth move sidelines chapter. This chapter will cover all of white's fourth moves that are not4.Nf3,4.Qc2or4.cxb5.  The good news for us is that as is the case with most of the course, there are very few critical lines that will cause us trouble in the sidelines areas. I will note for this chapter that there are many times where we will be transposing into the4.Nf3or4.Qc2chapters because we will be playing ...b4 against a lot of the fourth move options White can throw at us. Not all of them though!} 
4. Nd2 {The second-most popular 'fourth move sideline' option in the master database but objectively the best choice for White if they are not playing variations from the other chapters. White defends their c4-pawn and looks to play a quick e4. This move has some similarities to the 4. Qc2 variation (White also defends their c4-pawn and looks to play a quick e4 there too) but with one big difference which is our fourth move response.4...b4?!White can use the fact that the knight is on d2 to get in a very quick e4 and cause some trouble. Keeping the queen on d1 ends up being helpful for White in this particular variation.5.e4d66.f4!The pawn advance e5 is already tricky for us to deal with. If we compare this to the 4.Qc2 variation where White also pushes the central pawns quickly, we will see that ...Bf5 is not going to be coming with tempo at any point and with the queen still on d1, we cannot play ...Ng4 as easily.6...g67.e5dxe58.fxe5Ng4?9.e6+-The knight on g4 is not safe due to the queen still being on d1. If we compare this to the 4.Qc2 variation where the queen is not on d1, here we are in much more trouble.} 
4. bxc4 {A rare response in this chapter but an important one to memorize. We do not want to play ...b4 in this case because White has already committed their knight to d2 and part of the benefit of ...b4 is to keep the knight off c3. Also, if we play ...b4 here then White can cause us some trouble that we would rather not deal with. Rather than playing ...b4 we are going to capture on c4 against this variation.} 
5. Nxc4 {Capturing with the knight is not the best way for White to continue. Their pawn on d5 is now going to be difficult to defend.} 
5. Bb7
6. d6
6. Bd5
7. dxe7
7. Bxe7 {We have a big lead in development and are continuing to harass white's knight. Black is much better already.} 
