5. Nc3 {The most popular move where White wants to play e4 next. This doesn't bother us though since we are going to play 5...d5 against almost every move that White plays on move 5 in order to get the space advantage in the center of the board ourselves.} 
5. d5 {Preventing e4 from White and gaining space in the center.} 
6. cxd5
6. Nxd5 {We capture with the knight in order to avoid having an isolated queen pawn. Having an IQP is not necessarily a bad thing but here we can avoid it and have a good position. We are also making the positional threat of capturing on c3 and isolating white's queenside pawns.} 
7. Ndb5 {White tries to defend their knight on c3 and also 'threaten' Nxd5 and Nc7+ fork ideas. This backfires quickly though.} 
7. a6
8. e4
8. Nb4 {Anything you can do, I can do better! White still needs to solve their b5-knight problem since it is still attacked. We don't mind losing the ability to castle in this variation since our piece activity will make up for it.} 
9. Qxd8+ {9.Nd4??This walks into a tactic for Black.9...Qxd4!10.Qxd4Nc2+11.Kd1Nxd4-+Black emerges ahead a piece and should win easily.} 
9. Kxd8
10. Na3 {10.Nd4??This immediately blunders material.10...e5If the knight moves then ...Nc2+ picks up the a1-rook.11.a3exd412.axb4dxc3-+After playing some checkers with the pawns, we come out ahead a piece.} 
10. Bc5 {The position is pretty balanced but I prefer Black a bit due to white's knight on a3 being sidelined. We can put our king on e7, develop the queenside pieces and be in good shape going forward.} 
