1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. Nf3 {White decides not to play3.d5and thus avoid our Benko Gambit. Instead, they allow us to trade our c-pawn for their central d-pawn. As we know by now, playing3.d5is the critical line for White and anything else will give Black an easy game.} 
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e6 {Because of the c-pawn for d-pawn trade, the position resembles a Sicilian Defense a bit. One important difference though is that white's pawn is on c4 instead of e4. Our goal is to now not let the pawn advance to e4 easily and instead, look to gain a space advantage ourself in the center with our two central pawns.4...e55.Nb5d56.cxd5Bc5I was considering recommending this Vaganian Gambit variation which I have played a few times in the past but decided against it.  It is a fun variation that you may want to analyze on your own if it interests you but there is a lot of knowledge necessary for this variation and this type of gambit plays much differently from our usual Benko Gambit. What I am recommending with 4...e6 is much simpler and objectively better as well.} 
5. Nc3 {The most popular move where White wants to play e4 next. This doesn't bother us though since we are going to play 5...d5 against almost every move that White plays on move 5 in order to get the space advantage in the center of the board ourselves.} 
5. d5 {Preventing e4 from White and gaining space in the center.} 
6. cxd5
6. Nxd5 {We capture with the knight in order to avoid having an isolated queen pawn. Having an IQP is not necessarily a bad thing but here we can avoid it and have a good position. We are also making the positional threat of capturing on c3 and isolating white's queenside pawns.} 
7. Bd2 {White defends their knight with the bishop in order to avoid having isolated queenside pawns. The downside to this move is that it blocks their queen from influencing the center and doesn't put any pressure on us.} 
7. Be7 {This was played by Magnus Carlsen once and Wesley So a few times so it can't be a bad choice! We simply develop and prepare to castle kingside. White only has one way to stir up any trouble which is to play the pawn advance to e4.} 
8. e4
8. Nxc3
9. Bxc3
9. O-O {The position is fine for Black despite White having the space advantage in the center. We will play around the d-file quicker than White since we can play ...Qb6 and ...Rd8 soon.} 
10. Be2 {10.Bd3Qb6You can see an example of this position being played by Magnus Carlsen in one of the model games HERE.} 
10. Qb6
11. O-O
11. Rd8 {The d-file pin is a bit awkward for White.} 
12. Qb3
12. Qxb3
13. axb3 {White may capture with the a-pawn to open their rook but the doubled pawns are a long-term problem.} 
13. Bd7 {Next, we'll play ...Nc6 to trade more pieces and have a balanced position. The pawn structure advantage will be helpful later in the game.} 
