1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5 {Throughout the main chapters of the course we have focused on the third moves being3.d5(which we respond to with3...b5entering the Benko Gambit) and3.Nf3(which we respond to with3...cxd4). In this chapter we will be looking at all of the third move sidelines that are not3.d5or3.Nf3.  The good news for us is that all of the sidelines are very non-critical and will give us no problems at all. In most of these situations we should actually be able to get some kind of advantage for ourselves which will be pleasant.} 
3. dxc5 {White decides to capture our pawn but we are pretty much guaranteed to win it back.} 
3. e6 {If White doesn't try to hold onto the c-pawn then many of the variations will transpose into variations seen in the 2. Nf3 c5 Sidelines chapter.} 
4. Be3 {White tries to hold onto the pawn but we will get it back soon enough.} 
4. Na6
5. g3 {5.Nf3Nxc5I like taking on c5 with the knight after White has played Nf3. This is because we want to play ...b6 and ...Bb7 next and the knight on f3 makes it so that White doesn't beat us to it by playing g3 and Bg2 themselves.} 
5. Bxc5
