3. cxd4
4. Qxd4
4. Nc6 {Free development is always nice.} 
5. Qd2 {When White brings the queen back to this square then they are usually trying to play b3+Bb2 without leaving the bishop on b2 undefended. This set-up for White would be fine if we were to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 but the problem with the queen on d2 is that we can go for a pin with ...Bb4.} 
5. e6
6. a3 {White stops the pin but wastes precious time in the opening.} 
6. d5 {We look to open the center and use our lead in development.} 
7. cxd5
7. exd5 {We don't mind having an isolated d-pawn since this is a great version of it with white's queen being misplaced. Advancing with ...d4 is already an idea.} 
8. e3
8. Bd6 {The d-pawn is poisoned due to discovered attack tactics.} 
9. Nf3
9. O-O
10. Be2
10. Re8
11. O-O
11. Ne4 {We can take advantage of white's misplaced queen to stir up trouble.} 
12. Nxe4
12. dxe4
13. Nd4
13. Ne5 {We have more space on the kingside and a brewing attack. Our next moves may be ...Qg5 and ...Ng4. White needs to be very careful about their king safety.} 
