1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5 {Throughout the main chapters of the course we have focused on the third moves being3.d5(which we respond to with3...b5entering the Benko Gambit) and3.Nf3(which we respond to with3...cxd4). In this chapter we will be looking at all of the third move sidelines that are not3.d5or3.Nf3.  The good news for us is that all of the sidelines are very non-critical and will give us no problems at all. In most of these situations we should actually be able to get some kind of advantage for ourselves which will be pleasant.} 
3. e3 {The most popular sideline. White reinforces their d4-pawn with another pawn in order to keep the pawn center.} 
3. cxd4 {We trade pawns on d4 with the intention of playing ...d5 in the near future.} 
4. Qxd4 {I highly doubt anyone is playing 3. e3 and then capturing back on d4 with their queen afterwards but I want to be thorough and examine this as well.} 
4. Nc6 {We gain free development with a tempo on the queen.} 
5. Qd1
5. d5 {Now we work to open the center to use our lead in development.} 
6. cxd5 {White trades pawns and allows us to bring our queen into the center.} 
6. Qxd5
7. Qxd5
7. Nxd5
8. Bd2 {Preparing to play Nc3 without giving themselves an isolated c-pawn.} 
8. Ndb4 {We can threaten ...Nc2+ and mess up white's piece coordination.} 
9. Na3
9. e5 {We're in great shape here. We have the space advantage, white's a3-knight is misplaced, White cannot kick away our b4-knight, and the rook on a1 is also stuck defending the a2-pawn.} 
