1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5 {Throughout the main chapters of the course we have focused on the third moves being3.d5(which we respond to with3...b5entering the Benko Gambit) and3.Nf3(which we respond to with3...cxd4). In this chapter we will be looking at all of the third move sidelines that are not3.d5or3.Nf3.  The good news for us is that all of the sidelines are very non-critical and will give us no problems at all. In most of these situations we should actually be able to get some kind of advantage for ourselves which will be pleasant.} 
3. e3 {The most popular sideline. White reinforces their d4-pawn with another pawn in order to keep the pawn center.} 
3. cxd4 {We trade pawns on d4 with the intention of playing ...d5 in the near future.} 
4. exd4 {White recaptures with the pawn in order to control the center better.} 
4. g6 {We can hold off on playing ...d5 immediately and do it at a more opportune time. If you are comfortable playing against the Caro-Kann Panov Attack then you can play ...d5 anytime you would like to.4...d55.Nc3Transposes to a mainline of the Caro-Kann Panov Attack which can arise from1.e4c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.c4Nf65.Nc3.} 
5. Nc3
5. Bg7 {We will continue to hold off on ...d5. The plan is to make the advance after we have developed the bishop and castled.} 
6. Nf3
6. O-O
7. Be2 {White isn't playing d5 themselves so we will finally pull the trigger on it.} 
7. d5 {Challenging the center at an opportune time. By waiting until we have developed our bishop to g7 and castled, we take away a lot of the sting in white's set-up. If we had played ...d5 earlier then we would have to contend with cxd5 followed by Bc4 or Bb5+ follow-ups.} 
8. O-O
8. Nc6 {Black scores very nicely from this position in practical games. White will end up with an isolated d-pawn soon after we capture on c4. This version of the IQP is favorable for Black because usually White will try to do a kingside attack when they have this pawn structure and this is difficult to do with our fianchettoed bishop on g7.} 
9. c5 {White may decide to avoid the IQP structure and instead advance the pawn to c5 and turn it into a Panov structure. This plays differently from the IQP structure. Black's plan here is to target the d4-pawn which is a backward pawn and weakness.} 
9. Ne4 {We jump into the center since Nxe4 is not a good trade for White.} 
10. Be3
10. b6 {A common plan against this structure is to chip away at the c5-pawn and when it is traded off then the remaining pawn on d4 is simply isolated and weak.} 
11. cxb6
11. axb6 {The position is balanced but probably easier for us to play due to white's isolated d-pawn.   While it is true that our pawn on b6 is isolated too, it is difficult for White to attack it much while we can play moves like ...Ba6 to trade light-squared bishops and aim down the a-file towards the a2-pawn as well.} 
