6. d5 {The critical line, trying to punish us for not having played ...d5 ourselves yet. White prevents our advance and forces us to change gears a bit.} 
6. O-O
7. Nf3
7. e6 {An important move! The most common move in the database is to play7...d6but playing7...e6is much better. We immediately look to trade pawns and open the e-file and if we can eliminate White's d5-pawn then their space advantage will disappear.} 
8. dxe6 {White willingly trades off their d5-pawn which we're very happy to see.} 
8. dxe6 {We take back with the d-pawn to open the d-file.} 
9. Qxd8
9. Rxd8
10. Bf4 {White develops to control the dark squares but our development scheme doesn't change.} 
10. b6
11. Be2
11. Bb7
12. O-O
12. Ne4 {Our plan is the same as if the bishop was on e3. We want to trade off the c3-knight so that the b2-pawn is a target.} 
13. Nxe4
13. Bxe4
14. Ne5 {With the bishop on f4, it is possible for White to put a piece on e5 to block our diagonal.} 
14. Nd7 {Let's eliminate that pesky knight on e5.} 
15. Nxd7
15. Rxd7 {White cannot defend the b2-pawn in a productive way.} 
16. Bc1
16. Rc8 {White's pieces are completely passive and we can play ...Bd3 next to trade bishops and go after the c4-pawn.} 
