8. Be2
8. exd5 {We trade pawns to open the e-file and give White an isolated d-pawn.} 
9. Nxd5 {If White captures with a piece in order to avoid an isolated d-pawn then we can eventually use the bad position of white's queen to get an advantage.} 
9. Nxd5
10. Qxd5 {Without white's knight on c3 it is going to be difficult for White to develop their queenside since the b2-pawn will need to be defended first.} 
10. d6
11. O-O
11. Nc6
12. Rd1 {White targets our isolated d-pawn.} 
12. Re8 {We gain a tempo by harassing the bishop.} 
13. Bf1
13. Bf5 {We don't actually need to be concerned about the d-pawn since White capturing it will open an extra file for our more active pieces to use. Our d-pawn is a weakness anyways so there is actually some benefit in getting rid of it.} 
14. Qxd6
14. Qb6 {We avoid the queen trade and threaten ...Rad8 as well as ...Bxb2.} 
15. Qa3
15. a5 {The idea with ...a5 is to play ...Qb4 and trade queens and after taking back with the knight we want the knight on b4 to be defended so that Bd2 isn't possible.} 
16. c5
16. Qb4 {Usually you don't want to trade queens when you're down material but here white's queen was useful in defending the b2-pawn. If we had played ...Qc7 instead then White could respond with Be3 and their b2-pawn would be safe.} 
17. Qxb4
17. Nxb4 {Because the knight is defended then Bd2 doesn't gain a tempo for White. Here White has a difficult time keeping all of their pawns defended. The a2 and b2-pawns need protection and we can play ...Rac8 next to target the overextended c5-pawn. Playing ...Nc2 followed by a discovered attack is also in the air too.} 
