1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5
3. d5 {As we've seen throughout the course, almost all of the critical lines for White after we play ...c5 involve them advancing forward with their pawn to d5 and here it is no different.   White sidesteps our c-pawn and gains space in the center of the board. Rather than having the pawn on c4, they instead have a knight on f3 which does change things a bit.} 
3. b5 {I recommend playing in our typical Benko-style even though white's pawn is not on c4 yet. With our ...b5 advance here we are gaining queenside space and are ready to transpose into our Benko Gambit Declined chapters if White was to play c4 here. Instead, the more critical attempts for White involve playing for an early e4 advance and leaving their pawn off the c4-square in the meantime.} 
4. c3 {A rare move but it scores a very strong 68.5% for White in the database. This is also the recommendation of IM Christof Sielecki in one of his Chessable courses. Because of this, we should be prepared to face it. The idea behind this move is to play e4 next without allowing any of the ...Qa5+ ideas the would occur if White was to play 4. e4 instead.} 
4. g6 {White hasn't hit our b5-pawn yet so we continue with our usual development on the kingside.} 
5. e4
5. Nxe4 {We're generally happy to trade a central e4-pawn for our queenside b5-pawn.} 
6. Bxb5
6. Bg7
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. Re1
8. Nf6 {We go back to f6 rather than d6 so that we do not block our d-pawn and thus our queenside development. Also, the knight on f6 puts some pressure on white's d5-pawn.} 
9. c4 {Defending the d5-pawn more and opening up the c3-square for the knight.} 
9. d6 {Next we want to play ...a6, ...Nbd7-b6 and harass white's light-square bishop and c4/d5 pawns.} 
10. Nc3
10. a6 {Kicking the bishop back to a4 before playing ...Nbd7 is important. If we had played ...Nbd7 immediately then a4-a5 and Bc6 from White could be annoying.} 
11. Ba4
11. Nbd7 {Playing ...Nb6 with ...a5-a4 is coming.} 
12. Bg5
12. Nb6
13. Bb3 {Keeping the bishop and c4-pawn safe.} 
13. a5 {White's queen is a bit stuck to the d1 and c2 squares so that ...a4 doesn't become annoying to deal with. Next, we can play ...Ba6 or ...e6 in order to attack white's c4 and d5-pawns. Throwing in ...h6 will be useful too in order to kick around white's g5-bishop. White has a space advantage in the center here but their light-square bishop is misplaced and we have good chances to create pressure on white's position with a few different pawn moves.} 
