3. d5 {As we've seen throughout the course, almost all of the critical lines for White after we play ...c5 involve them advancing forward with their pawn to d5 and here it is no different.   White sidesteps our c-pawn and gains space in the center of the board. Rather than having the pawn on c4, they instead have a knight on f3 which does change things a bit.} 
3. b5 {I recommend playing in our typical Benko-style even though white's pawn is not on c4 yet. With our ...b5 advance here we are gaining queenside space and are ready to transpose into our Benko Gambit Declined chapters if White was to play c4 here. Instead, the more critical attempts for White involve playing for an early e4 advance and leaving their pawn off the c4-square in the meantime.} 
4. Bg5 {The most popular move by a big margin where White develops their bishop before playing Nbd2. The intention is to threaten Bxf6 doubling our f-pawns. Some of the most popular responses here (4...Qb6 and 4...Ne4) are tailored towards avoiding the doubled f-pawns.} 
4. g6 {A rare move in the databse for this position but the best option! We don't mind the potential doubled f-pawns. In that way, this variation has some similarities to the Trompowsky. We intend to develop our bishop to g7 to strike along the open diagonal.} 
5. d6 {The critical test for this variation. This will require some memorization of specific moves rather than general ideas on our part. Fortunately for us, this move has only been played in the database 8 times compared to 5. Bxf6 which has been played close to 90 times. Surprisingly, this move was first played back in 1977 but hasn't been popularized at all. Probably this is because our move 4...g6 is already on the rare side of things. White's idea with d6 here is to weaken the d5-square by pulling our e-pawn off the e-file or trading dxe7.} 
5. exd6 {We take the pawn and plan to hold onto it for a while, only giving it back when it benefits us. This was played in the original 1977 game and surprisingly never since then!} 
6. Nc3 {White takes aim at the weakened d5-square and b5-pawn. We need to be precise now.} 
6. Be7 {The only good move! We switch gears and develop the bishop to e7 rather than g7 since we need to break the pin on the g5-d8 diagonal. We don't mind if White captures the b5-pawn because the focus is the central light squares instead.} 
7. Nxb5 {White grabs the pawn and aims at our d6-pawn.} 
7. Qa5+ {Forcing the knight back to c3.} 
8. Nc3
8. d5 {Now we threaten ...d4 winning the pinned knight.The pawn cannot be won with9.Bxf6Bxf6and10.Qxd5since10...Bxc3+would be our response.} 
9. e3
9. Nc6 {Threatening ...d4 once again since the g5-bishop would be hanging after the series of captures on d4.} 
10. Qd2 {White breaks the pin but allows us to trade a few pieces.} 
10. Ne4
11. Nxe4
11. dxe4
12. Qxa5
12. Nxa5
13. Bxe7
13. Kxe7
14. Nd2
14. d5 {Material is equal and our pawns are no longer doubled. The resulting endgame is fairly balanced but we have good chances to win with our space advantage here. Next we'll play ...Be6, ...f5 and develop the rooks towards the queenside.} 
