6. Be7 {The only good move! We switch gears and develop the bishop to e7 rather than g7 since we need to break the pin on the g5-d8 diagonal. We don't mind if White captures the b5-pawn because the focus is the central light-squares instead.} 
7. e3 {White opens up their bishop to hit the b5-pawn.} 
7. a6 {If White doesn't take b5 immediately then we'll be greedy and hold onto it.} 
8. a4 {White tries to provoke weaknesses on the light-squares with this move. They want us to play ...b4 which would allow White to play Bc4 later.} 
8. b4 {We go along with their idea.} 
9. Bxf6 {White eliminates our knight that is controlling the light-squares in the center.} 
9. Bxf6
10. Ne4 {The best square for the knight where it hits the d6-pawn.10.Nd5?Bxb211.Rb1Bg7∓We're ahead two pawns and white's compensation isn't significant enough to make up for this.} 
10. O-O {We need to evacuate the king out of the center before Nxd6 comes with a check.} 
11. Rb1 {White defends the b2-pawn first, knowing that the d6-pawn isn't going anywhere.} 
11. Bb7 {Activating the bishop before the knight lands on d6 which would take away the b7-square.} 
12. Nxd6
12. Bc6
13. Bc4 {13.b3?Trying to hold on to the a4-pawn backfires very quickly.13...Bc3+14.Nd2Qe715.Nc4d516.Nb2d4-+We are in full control now and have a completely dominant position.} 
13. Qc7 {We plan to kick the knight off the d6-square with ...Be7 next move.} 
14. Qd3 {White prepares to play Rd1 to reinforce the knight.} 
14. Be7
15. Rd1
15. Bxd6
16. Qxd6
16. Qxd6
17. Rxd6
17. Bxa4 {We get to pick off a pawn. Despite White having very good piece activity and compensation for this pawn, this is a position where we are actually on the other side of the board in terms of compensation! Not a common occurrence in this course :-)} 
18. b3
18. Bb5 {Looking to trade pieces.} 
19. Ne5
19. Nc6 {We activate our knight at the cost of the d7-pawn.} 
20. Nxd7
20. Rfd8
21. Bxb5
21. axb5 {The back-rank skewer with ...Ra1 is a big threat now.} 
22. Ke2
22. Ne5 {We rush to trade knights and rooks in order to get into a drawish endgame.} 
23. Nf6+
23. Kg7
24. Rxd8
24. Rxd8
25. Ne4
25. Ra8 {We grab the furthest open file from white's king, knowing that Nxc5 isn't a threat due to ...Rc8 where we win the c2-pawn back with check. Next we will play ...Ra2 or ...c4 and the endgame is very balanced.   Overall, I wouldn't be concerned about this 5. d6 variation much at all since it is incredibly rare. It does require the most memorization in the course to get through these variations but objectively Black is okay if we know what we're doing.   On the other hand, White has to find a lot of strong moves themselves to get this far into the variations as well.} 
