8. Bd3 {Rather than putting the bishop on b5, White may develop it to d3. This is a much more common approach for White to play but objectively not as challenging for us as Black.} 
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. d6 {We're ready to play ...f5 next move if White doesn't defend the b2-pawn or get more control over the e5-square. If ...f5 is prevented then ...Nd7-b6 or ...Bg4xf3 are our other ideas (in that order).} 
10. Rb1 {White defends their b2-pawn but doesn't stop ...Nd7-b6.} 
10. Nd7
11. Nc4
11. Nb6 {Challenging white's best minor piece which is the knight on c4. Now we threaten to play ...Nxc4 followed by .. .f5 since the d3-bishop would be pulled away.} 
12. Nfd2 {White reinforces their knight on c4.} 
12. f5 {We can play this advance anyways since the d5-pawn will get undermined.} 
13. exf5
13. Bb7 {We don't capture the d5-pawn yet since a pin with Be4 would annoy us. Instead, we want to capture the d5-pawn with our bishop.} 
14. Be4
14. Re8 {If you want to play for a win then this is what I recommend. We may not be guaranteed to win back our pawn but our piece activity will compensate for it.14...Ba6If you're okay with a draw then this is playable too.15.Bd3Bb7With a potential repetition.} 
15. Qf3
15. Qe7 {Continuing to apply pressure to the e4-bishop and threatening to play ...Nxc4 winning a piece. We are always fine with White playing Nxb6 since it would open up our rook on the a-file towards white's a2-pawn.} 
16. Rfe1 {Now white's e4-bishop is somewhat pinned.} 
16. Ba6 {Attacking the c4-knight since Bd3 is no longer an option.} 
17. Na5
17. Qg5 {Now the d2-knight is a target.} 
18. Red1
18. Nd7 {White is tied down to protecting all their weaknesses and soft spots including the b2-pawn, e4-bishop and d2-knight. We can play ...Ne5, double rooks on the e-file and continue to apply pressure to white's position. Despite being down a pawn, our compensation is nice and we have good chances to create problems for White from here.} 
