[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 b5"]
[Black "2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4.Bg5 #25"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5
3. d5 {As we've seen throughout the course, almost all of the critical lines for White after we play ...c5 involve them advancing forward with their pawn to d5 and here it is no different.   White sidesteps our c-pawn and gains space in the center of the board. Rather than having the pawn on c4, they instead have a knight on f3 which does change things a bit.} 
3. b5 {I recommend playing in our typical Benko-style even though white's pawn is not on c4 yet. With our ...b5 advance here we are gaining queenside space and are ready to transpose into our Benko Gambit Declined chapters if White was to play c4 here. Instead, the more critical attempts for White involve playing for an early e4 advance and leaving their pawn off the c4-square in the meantime.} 
4. Bg5 {The most popular move by a big margin where White develops their bishop before playing Nbd2. The intention is to threaten Bxf6 doubling our f-pawns. Some of the most popular responses here (4...Qb6 and 4...Ne4) are tailored towards avoiding the doubled f-pawns.} 
4. g6 {A rare move in the databse for this position but the best option! We don't mind the potential doubled f-pawns. In that way, this variation has some similarities to the Trompowsky. We intend to develop our bishop to g7 to strike along the open diagonal.} 
5. Bxf6 {White doubles the pawns but has to give up one of their bishops to do so.} 
5. exf6 {Despite having doubled pawns, we will use them effectively by working towards playing ...f5 in many variations.} 
6. e4 {White gains more space in the center and attacks our b5-pawn.} 
6. b4 {Our typical response to the b5-pawn being attacked. The more common move in this position is6...a6but I don't think this move helps us much since White will usually play7.a4afterwards and we are forced to play7...b4at that point anyways.} 
7. Nbd2 {White develops the knight and plans to maneuver it to the c4-square later.} 
7. Bg7
8. Bd3 {Rather than putting the bishop on b5, White may develop it to d3. This is a much more common approach for White to play but objectively not as challenging for us as Black.} 
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. d6 {We're ready to play ...f5 next move if White doesn't defend the b2-pawn or get more control over the e5-square. If ...f5 is prevented then ...Nd7-b6 or ...Bg4xf3 are our other ideas (in that order).} 
10. Nc4 {White defends the b2-pawn and discourages ...f5 as well as ... Nd7-b6 since the d6-pawn would be undefended. Because of this, we go with our third plan of ...Bg4xf3.} 
10. Bg4 {Looking to eliminate the f3-knight and play ...Nd7-e5 or ...Nd7-b6 to trade off the other knight.10...Qc7You can see an example of this position being played in one of the model games by Daniil Dubov HERE.} 
11. h3
11. Bxf3
12. Qxf3
12. Nd7 {The d6-pawn is poisoned due to ... Ne5 winning a piece.} 
13. Qg3
13. Ne5 {Aiming to trade knights on c4 then play ...f5 once the c4-knight is gone.} 
14. Nxe5 {Trading knights fixes our doubled pawns and actually gives us a pleasant position.} 
14. fxe5 {Both bishops are bad but we have the easier pawn breaks to work towards playing (...f5 and ... a5-a4-a3) and can activate our bishop on the h6-square to be a bit more useful. The position is objectively equal but I think we can press White a bit here.} 
