[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2.Nf3 c5 Sidelines"]
[Black "2. Nf3 c5 3.c3 d5 4.dxc5 e6 5.Be3 Nc6 6.b4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5 {Now we'll be looking at all of the sidelines after 2. Nf3 c5. The good news for us is that 3. d5 is the only critical move in the position so all of the sidelines will be very pleasant for us! Also good to know is that the sidelines do get played a lot of the time so that is extra-good for us :-)} 
3. c3 {Many people who play the London System will try to get to their normal set-up (d4, Nf3, Bf4) with this move order starting with 2. Nf3. This move order is a bit tougher for us to crack with our 2...c5 advance since playing something like ...Qb6 here doesn't make any sense due to the b2-pawn still being defended. That being said, I think I've still come up with a good way to combat the London system set-up that White may go for.} 
3. d5
4. dxc5 {Objectively white's best move but not very popular. The idea is to be a bit greedy and try to hold onto the c5-pawn and make it difficult for Black to equalize material.} 
4. e6
5. Be3 {The most difficult move for Black. It ends up that White will most likely be able to keep their extra pawn but it will come at the cost of some weaknesses in their position.} 
5. Nc6 {We prepare to play ...Ng4 to eliminate white's bishop that is defending their c5-pawn.5...Ng4??Don't go after the bishop immediately if you don't want to lose the game on the spot!6.Qa4++-Goodbye knight :-)} 
6. b4 {White reinforces their c5-pawn.} 
6. Be7 {For now we should focus on developing our pieces. White has used a lot of moves to win and hold onto the c5-pawn and we can get a lead in development in response.} 
7. Nbd2 {White develops their b1-knight but blocks any retreat squares from their e3-bishop.} 
7. O-O {White has a bit of a tough time developing their kingside bishop and castling with the bishop on the e3-square.} 
8. g3 {I could easily see this mistake being made.} 
8. Ng4 {The bishop on e3 is in trouble now.} 
9. Bg2
9. Nxe3
10. fxe3
10. a5
11. a3
11. b6 {White is up a pawn but has a terrible pawn structure and we also have the bishop pair. Black is in great shape here.} 
