11. Nxe5
11. Nxe5
12. O-O
12. b6 {Now we finally get rid of the c5-pawn.} 
13. cxb6
13. axb6 {We have remained down a pawn but have good compensation based on the control of the half-open a- and c-files towards the pawns on a2 and c3. Our control over the c4-square is good too and white's queenside development isn't so easy to accomplish. Next we can play ...Bb7, ...Qd7, ...Rfc8 and play around the queenside part of the board.} 
