2. c5 {Now we'll be looking at all of the sidelines after 2. Nf3 c5. The good news for us is that 3. d5 is the only critical move in the position so all of the sidelines will be very pleasant for us! Also good to know is that the sidelines do get played a lot of the time so that is extra-good for us :-)} 
3. e3 {White reinforces their d4-pawn but blocks in their c1-bishop and doesn't fight for the center immediately. For this reason, we should go ahead and take the center.} 
3. d5 {Gaining a space advantage as Black in most openings should be difficult to accomplish if White is playing ambitiously but if our opponent is playing passively then we should be taking the center ourselves.} 
4. c4 {White may try to break in the center with c4 now but this comes a bit too late for us to be bothered.} 
4. cxd4 {By capturing on d4, we pretty much force White to recapture with their e-pawn since all other moves are bad in comparison.} 
5. exd4 {We are now in a variation from the Caro-Kann which can be reached through the move order1.e4c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.c4Nf65.Nf3. This variation is known to not cause Black much trouble.White will most likely end up with an isolated d-pawn in the near future and for this reason I like developing the bishop to g7 to keep our kingside more defended.5.Nxd4?!White is asking to be hit with ...e5 here.5...e5!6.Nf3Nc6⩱We simply have a space advantage without any problem. Playing ...d4 may come next if White does nothing to stop it.5.Qxd4?!Now the queen is an easy target.5...Nc66.Qd1e5⩱We get the same position as the 5.Nxd4?! clickable variation.5.cxd5This loses a pawn.5...dxe36.Bxe3Nxd57.Bc4e6White has some compensation with a lead in development but they are down a pawn and we can finish our development pretty quickly with ...Bb4+ or ...Be7 followed by castling and then working to get our queenside pieces in the game. The extra pawn will eventually be great for us.} 
5. g6 {The game plan is to play ...Bg7, ...O-O, trade the c4/d5 pawns and play against white's isolated d-pawn.} 
