2. c5 {Now we'll be looking at all of the sidelines after 2. Nf3 c5. The good news for us is that 3. d5 is the only critical move in the position so all of the sidelines will be very pleasant for us! Also good to know is that the sidelines do get played a lot of the time so that is extra-good for us :-)} 
3. e3 {White reinforces their d4-pawn but blocks in their c1-bishop and doesn't fight for the center immediately. For this reason, we should go ahead and take the center.} 
3. d5 {Gaining a space advantage as Black in most openings should be difficult to accomplish if White is playing ambitiously but if our opponent is playing passively then we should be taking the center ourselves.} 
4. c3 {White goes for the Colle system with the f2-d4-b2 pawn triangle which is solid but very unambitious. In my opinion, this is simply a worse London system since the bishop is shut in on c1 rather than active on f4.   Against this system, the typical way to gain a bigger advantage as Black is to work towards the ...e5 pawn advance and grab even more space in the center. This is part of the reason for our next move.} 
4. Nbd7 {I like the development scheme of putting the knight on d7, bishop on g7, castling kingside, queen on c7 and working towards the ...e5 pawn advance. White has a very passive set-up that is not well equipped for dealing with this plan.   Another advantage of this setup is that most Colle system players try to make their plan around the idea of O-O, Nbd2, Ne5, f4 and a kingside attack. With our bishop on g7 and pawn on g6, this attack is much less dangerous since white's bishop on d3 will have a smaller diagonal and only be aiming at a well-defended g6-pawn.} 
5. Bd3 {The move order for White doesn't really make too much difference to us. If they play Nbd2 first or Bd3 first, our response will be the same.} 
5. g6
6. Nbd2 {Playing Nbd2 and castling kingside is interchangeable here. Again, our set-up as Black is consistent.} 
6. Bg7
7. O-O
7. O-O {Now here we're at a bit of a crossroad. White has many different moves they can try here. Against most of them our plan of playing ...Qc7 and ...e5 will be consistent. There are a few moves that can alter things though that we should be aware of.} 
8. b3 {White may try to develop the bishop to b2 but we will get in the ...e5 pawn break quickly.} 
8. Qc7
9. Bb2
9. e5 {We charge in the center and threaten ... e4.} 
10. dxe5
10. Nxe5
11. Nxe5
11. Qxe5
12. Nf3 {White could instead play12.Qc2which defends their b2-bishop and prepares to play c4 next. In response, we can simply play12...Qe7to get our queen off the diagonal of white’s bishop.} 
12. Qe7
13. c4 {White gets to open up their b2-bishop but our bishop on g7 is well equipped to battle against it.} 
13. Rd8 {The position is balanced but we have a slight space advantage with two pawns on the fifth rank compared to white's one pawn on the fourth rank. The d-file will also open soon and our rook on d8 will be well-positioned. We're immediately threatening to capture on c4 and White has to be a bit careful here.} 
