[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bf4 {The London System is a very solid opening that has become mainstream over the past years. White usually looks to set up a triangle of pawns from f2-e3-d4-c3-b2 with their pieces typically being developed with Bf4, Nf3, Bd3, Nbd2 in some order. This opening is tough to crack and get any objective advantage against White's best play.   However, White usually plays the opening in a non-ambitious way and doesn't really put much pressure on Black until the middlegame arises. With this in mind, we are actually going to be trying to put pressure on White earlier in the game so that we can distract them from their typical autopilot set-up.} 
2. c5 {Immediately striking at the center using our typical 2...c5 pawn break. White usually plays e3 here but there are a few other options for us to be ready to play against.} 
3. d5 {This is white's best option but3.e3is much more popular by a big margin. Here with3.d5White is gaining more space in the center of the board and preventing us from playing ...d5 ourselves.} 
3. b5 {We play in the style of the Benko Gambit with an early ...b5 advance! White has a few different moves possible that we should be prepared for but nothing we can't handle.} 
4. c4
4. b4 {Similar to the 4. a4 variation, we want to shut down the queenside, put our bishop on g7 and look to focus our play around the kingside later on.} 
5. Nd2
5. d6
6. e4
6. g6
7. Be2 {Playing7.e5and opening the center immediately is not a problem for us. We can respond with7...dxe58.Bxe5and play ...Nbd7 at any point to gain a free tempo due to attacking the bishop on e5.} 
7. Bg7
8. h3 {8.Ngf3?A typical tactical mistake that White must be careful about.8...Nh5∓White cannot defend the f4-bishop and b2-pawn at the same time and loses material. This move works since the knight on f3 blocks off White's e2-bishop from defending the h5-square.} 
8. O-O
9. Qc2
9. a5
10. Ngf3
10. Nh5
11. Be3
11. e5 {Wait a second...Didn't I mention the benefit of the bishop being on an open diagonal towards b2? Why are we blocking the bishop in now? Let me explain: The idea here is that because the queenside is locked up then the majority of the play for the rest of the game will revolve around the kingside.   When we play ...e5, it is now easier for us to play the pawn break ...f5 and attack on the kingside similar to a King's Indian Defense middlegame.   White has no counterplay on the queenside and Black has an easier time playing this position. In fact, the computer says that white's best move is to capture en passant and open our bishop up again!} 
12. dxe6 {12.O-O?!If White doesn't capture en passant then we will blast through with a kingside attack in the near future.12...Nf413.Rfe1Nxe2+14.Rxe2f5-+Black is already significantly better. Our immediate threat is ...f4 trapping the bishop and even if White avoids this threat then we will still play ...f4 followed by ...g5 and attack on the kingside.15.Nf1f416.Bd2a4∓Now if White plays a3 or b3 then we can respond by locking the queenside completely. Next is ... Ra7-f7 or g7, ...g5, ...h5, ...g4 and a huge attack.} 
12. fxe6 {Keeping control over the d5-square and opening up our f8-rook. Next we will play ...Nf4, ...Nc6, ...a4 and play around the weak dark-squares in white's position.} 
