7. Qb6 {Black has an extra pawn but White has a lead in development and a slight space advantage in the center. The game is dynamically balanced and it will be a dogfight to get through the remainder of the opening unscathed. However, if we do so then we'll be up a pawn going into the later stages of the game.} 
8. a4
8. b4
9. h4 {Discouraging us from playing ...g6 and ...Bg7.} 
9. Bb7 {Black is going to build pressure on the d5-pawn which is a bit of a sitting duck in the center of the board.} 
10. Bc4 {Reinforcing the pawn on d5.} 
10. Ba6 {It may seem weird to play ...Bb7 then play ...Ba6 on the next move but the key here is that once White has developed their bishop to c4 then it is undefended and we create the threat of capturing it. If we had played ...Ba6 when white's bishop was on f1 then White wouldn't need to react to our move since the bishop on f1 would be protected.} 
11. Bxa6
11. Qxa6 {We capture back with the queen in order to control the a6-f1 diagonal. The knight will develop to d7 after we play ...d6 later. Next we will play ...g6 and fianchetto the dark-square bishop. If White plays h5 here then we can instead focus on developing the queenside pieces first with ...d6, ...Nd7 and ...Rc8.} 
