[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) London System 2.Bf4"]
[Black "2.Bf4 c5 3.d5 b5 4.a4 b4 5.c4 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bf4 {The London System is a very solid opening that has become mainstream over the past years. White usually looks to set up a triangle of pawns from f2-e3-d4-c3-b2 with their pieces typically being developed with Bf4, Nf3, Bd3, Nbd2 in some order. This opening is tough to crack and get any objective advantage against White's best play.   However, White usually plays the opening in a non-ambitious way and doesn't really put much pressure on Black until the middlegame arises. With this in mind, we are actually going to be trying to put pressure on White earlier in the game so that we can distract them from their typical autopilot set-up.} 
2. c5 {Immediately striking at the center using our typical 2...c5 pawn break. White usually plays e3 here but there are a few other options for us to be ready to play against.} 
3. d5 {This is white's best option but3.e3is much more popular by a big margin. Here with3.d5White is gaining more space in the center of the board and preventing us from playing ...d5 ourselves.} 
3. b5 {We play in the style of the Benko Gambit with an early ...b5 advance! White has a few different moves possible that we should be prepared for but nothing we can't handle.} 
4. a4 {The most common move in the database but not the best. White is trying to get rid of the b-pawn before playing c4. The downside here is that we don't need to get rid of the b-pawn and can instead advance it.} 
4. b4
5. c4 {Most games have gone this route but Black is already a bit better off at this point. This is because of the queenside space advantage and the wide open diagonal for our bishop once it gets to the g7-square.} 
5. d6
6. Nd2
6. g6
7. e4
7. Bg7 {We will see positions like this in the 2.Nf3 c5 3.d5 b5 as well. These positions are more pleasant for Black since it is hard for White to make use of their space advantage and we will counterattack on the kingside. Usually in these pawn structures White wants to play on the queenside but with the queenside pawns completely locked up this proves impossible to do.} 
8. Qc2 {Keep in mind that we’re not concerned about White playing a quick8.e5since8...Nh5!would win a pawn due to the attack on white’s bishop and discovered attack on their e5-pawn.} 
8. b3 {A very nice pawn sacrifice. The idea here is to open up the b-file towards the b2-pawn target. If White doesn't capture the pawn then we will use the newly opened b4-square for our knight.} 
9. Qb1
9. Na6 {White will probably be forced to capture the b-pawn at some point to prevent ...Nb4-c2+ but then we will attack down the b-file towards the b2-pawn.} 
