3. Qb6
4. Nc3
4. d6 {This is the most popular move and best scoring move so I figured this was an easy recommendation. Black can play simply from here by developing the bishop to g7, putting the queenside knight on d7, dropping the queen back to c7 if necessary and looking to use the pawn break ...e5 at the right time to put more pressure on white's center.} 
5. Bb5+ {White usually makes this check that blocks off our queen from attacking the b2-pawn.} 
5. Nbd7 {I recommend blocking with the knight on d7 rather than the bishop. This is because we want to harass white's bishop next move with ...a6 and not give them an easy escape by trading bishops on d7. We want the bishop to have to retreat back to d3 or somewhere else instead. The knight on d7 will also support ...e5 advances in the near future.} 
6. a4 {White needs to play a4-a5 in order to kick our queen away from the b-file where we aim at the b2-pawn.} 
6. a6
7. a5
7. Qc7
8. Be2 {White avoids trading their bishop for the knight.} 
8. g6
9. d5 {White may shutdown the center with the d5-pawn advance and aim to get us into a Benoni structure but this actually ends up being pretty good for us since our bishop on g7 will be a monster.} 
9. Bg7
10. e4
10. b5 {We immediately expand on the queenside before White gets to develop their knight and castle. Playing ...b4 and then ...Nxe4 is our immediate threat.} 
11. axb6 {White cannot afford to leave our b5-pawn alive.} 
11. Qxb6 {Now we have a half-open b-file aiming directly at white's b2-pawn.} 
12. Ra2
12. Qb4 {Because we played ...b5 before castling we now have this option which makes life difficult for White. We threaten to capture the e4-pawn and White has only one good way to defend it.} 
13. f3 {Defending the e4-pawn but the knight cannot develop to f3 anymore.13.Qd3??This defense fails tactically.13...Nxe414.Qxe4Bxc3+-+The queen on e4 is captured next.} 
13. O-O {We have a pleasant position with the Benoni pawn structure. White's position is under some pressure due to our active pieces. Next, we can play ...Nb6 which will threaten ...Nfxd5 due to the pins along the e1-b4 diagonal and b4-f4 rank.} 
