1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. c5 {Now we'll be looking at all of the sidelines after 2. Nf3 c5. The good news for us is that 3. d5 is the only critical move in the position so all of the sidelines will be very pleasant for us! Also good to know is that the sidelines do get played a lot of the time so that is extra-good for us :-)} 
3. c3 {Many people who play the London System will try to get to their normal set-up (d4, Nf3, Bf4) with this move order starting with 2. Nf3. This move order is a bit tougher for us to crack with our 2...c5 advance since playing something like ...Qb6 here doesn't make any sense due to the b2-pawn still being defended. That being said, I think I've still come up with a good way to combat the London system set-up that White may go for.} 
3. d5
4. Bf4 {White gets a version of the London System that is a bit different from what is recommended in the main London System chapter. The main difference is due to the pawns being on ...d5 and c3. That being said, Black is doing well in this version of things as long as we go for quick play against White's b2-pawn soon.} 
4. Qb6 {Immediately threatening to capture on b2 since White's bishop is no longer defending the pawn.} 
5. Qc2
5. cxd4 {5...Bf5??This move doesn't work when the c8-square is left undefended.6.Qxf5Qxb27.Qc8#!} 
6. cxd4
6. Nc6
7. Nc3 {White develops a piece and is prepared to sacrifice their d4-pawn.} 
7. a6 {Defending the b5-square another time and now threatening to capture on d4.7...Nxd4?!Capturing the d4 pawn is very risky due to our lack of development.8.Nxd4Qxd49.e4±White opens the center of the board and is ready to use their lead in development to give us a lot of trouble. The threat is Nb5 and we already have a tough time dealing with things.} 
8. e3
8. Bf5 {This is a consistent trick in our aresenal in order to pull the queen away from the b2-pawn.} 
9. Bd3 {The computer says this is white's best option but we are still happy after the following sequence.9.Qb3?!Qxb310.axb3Rc8⩱Even though we open the a-file for white’s rook, this is a good pawn structure for Black. We were able to give White double isolated b-pawns. Next, we’ll play ...e6, develop the bishop and castle.9.Qd2?!e6⩱White's queen is now misplaced and will run into trouble with a future ...Bb4 or ...Ne4 move. Black is already slightly preferred here.} 
9. Nb4
10. Qa4+
10. Bd7
11. Qd1
11. Nxd3+
12. Qxd3
12. Rc8 {We're now threatening to capture on b2 since the knight on c3 will be under attack afterwards. We have the bishop pair and no weaknesses. Black should be at least a little bit better going forward after we complete our kingside development.} 
