3. d5
4. Bf4 {White gets a version of the London System that is a bit different from what is recommended in the main London System chapter. The main difference is due to the pawns being on ...d5 and c3. That being said, Black is doing well in this version of things as long as we go for quick play against White's b2-pawn soon.} 
4. Qb6 {Immediately threatening to capture on b2 since White's bishop is no longer defending the pawn.} 
5. Qb3 {White's most popular location for the queen to defend against the threat on b2.} 
5. Nc6 {We don't mind leaving the tension between the queens for now. We will only capture on b3 if we can give White isolated pawns. White usually doesn't want to capture us on b6 either since it will open up our a8-rook. We will usually play ...c4 next to force white's queen to make a decision.} 
6. e3 {White's most popular move but already a bit of a mistake! Now we get a pleasant advantage due to a typical idea.} 
6. c4
7. Qxb6 {Trading queens on b6 will give Black an advantageous pawn structure.} 
7. axb6 {Black is better now despite having doubled b-pawns. These pawns will be useful in the near future since we can quickly play ...b5-b4 to chip away at white's b2-d4 pawn chain. Our rook is also open on the a-file now.} 
8. Na3 {White tries to prevent the ...b5-b4 plan but it will not be stopped forever.} 
8. Bf5 {Developing and covering the c2-square.} 
9. Nb5 {White threatens a fork on c7 but we can defend against this with a nice counterattack.} 
9. Ra5
10. a4 {10.Nc7+?The knight will have trouble escaping from here.10...Kd7Playing ...e6 followed by ...Bd6 is a big threat to win the knight on c7. White doesn't really have a great way to play from here without losing some kind of material.11.Ne5+Nxe512.dxe5Nh5-+Next, we'll take the bishop or knight. The rook defends the d5-pawn on a5, so white's knight is trapped.} 
10. e6 {We can calmly develop and look to play ...Bc2 at some point to target the a4-pawn. We may also play ...Kd7 and a later ...Rha8 to attack a4 as well.} 
11. Be2 {11.Nd6+?Bxd612.Bxd6Kd713.Bg3Rha8-+White's a4-pawn is lost.Playing11...Bc2here doesn’t win the pawn since White can respond with12.Bd1.} 
11. Be7
12. Bd1 {White tries to defend the a4-pawn but their pieces will end up very passive.} 
12. Kd7
13. O-O
13. Rha8 {Threatening ...Rxb5 due to the pin on the a-file.} 
14. Rc1
14. Bd3
15. Re1
15. Ne4 {White's pieces are completely frozen and next we will play ...f6, ...g5 and increase the pressure.} 
