[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Trompowsky"]
[Black "2.Bg5 c5 3.d5 Ne4 4.Bc1 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky can be a good surprise weapon for players who want to avoid mainline opening theory and still get a game with interesting imbalances. Typically White is looking to trade the bishop for knight on f6 which results in the imbalance of Black having a compromised doubled-pawn structure but in return Black gains the bishop pair.} 
2. c5 {The move I'm recommending is 2...c5 which keeps our opening repertoire easy to remember. We're going to play 2...c5 against almost every move that White can throw at us.   There will be a few exceptions to this but that will tend to be the game plan. The idea behind 2...c5 is that we want to start a fight against White's d4-pawn as quickly as possible.   If we can chip away at it then we can look to gain a space advantage ourselves in the center as the game progresses. Also, we open up the d8-a5 diagonal for our queen which will tend to go towards the b6-square in a lot of situations. From b6 the queen will put more pressure on the d4-pawn as well as the undefended b2-pawn.} 
3. d5 {A very natural move where White avoids the trade of pawns and gains more space. As we see in the mainlines of the Benko Gambit, this d5-pawn becomes a target and we can chip away at it with ...e6 soon.} 
3. Ne4
4. Bc1
4. e6 {Chipping away at white's center.} 
5. c4
5. b5 {We can continue in Benko-style here in order to have all the fun!} 
6. dxe6
6. fxe6
7. cxb5
7. c4 {Opening up the dark-square bishop. We may continue with ...a6 in Benko-style soon too.} 
