[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky can be a good surprise weapon for players who want to avoid mainline opening theory and still get a game with interesting imbalances. Typically White is looking to trade the bishop for knight on f6 which results in the imbalance of Black having a compromised doubled-pawn structure but in return Black gains the bishop pair.} 
2. c5 {The move I'm recommending is 2...c5 which keeps our opening repertoire easy to remember. We're going to play 2...c5 against almost every move that White can throw at us.   There will be a few exceptions to this but that will tend to be the game plan. The idea behind 2...c5 is that we want to start a fight against White's d4-pawn as quickly as possible.   If we can chip away at it then we can look to gain a space advantage ourselves in the center as the game progresses. Also, we open up the d8-a5 diagonal for our queen which will tend to go towards the b6-square in a lot of situations. From b6 the queen will put more pressure on the d4-pawn as well as the undefended b2-pawn.} 
3. d5 {A very natural move where White avoids the trade of pawns and gains more space. As we see in the mainlines of the Benko Gambit, this d5-pawn becomes a target and we can chip away at it with ...e6 soon.} 
3. Ne4
4. h4 {The 'Raptor' variation! It tends to be that variations named after animals are usually not good but I've played this one as White a few times and Kamil Plichta recommends this in his Trompowsky course too.} 
4. h6 {Poking the bishop and kicking it back a bit.} 
5. Bf4
5. Qb6 {Targeting the weak b2-pawn. This is a common idea to keep in mind when the bishop has left c1 and we have the d8-a5 diagonal open.} 
6. Nd2
6. Qxb2 {We can afford to be greedy here!} 
7. Nxe4
7. Qb4+
8. c3
8. Qxe4 {Our queen is vulnerable in the center but we are gaining some tempo by attacking pieces along the way.} 
9. e3
9. e5 {Gaining space, attacking the bishop and looking to shutdown the center with ...d6 next.} 
10. dxe6 {10.Bg3?!d6∓It is surprisingly difficult for White to harass our queen. Playing f3 will leave the pawn on e3 undefended while playing Bd3 will leave the pawn on g2 undefended.  We are ahead a pawn and once we develop then we will be very happy.10.f3White kicks our queen but allows us to keep the pawn on e5 which shuts down a bit of their activity.10...Qf511.g4Qf612.Bg3d6Black has an extra pawn and I don't see White having quite enough compensation to make up for it.} 
10. dxe6
11. Nf3
11. Nd7 {This may seem like an awkward square for the knight to develop to but we want to leave the c6 square open for our queen if it gets attacked. Later the light-square bishop may be developed with ...b6 and ...Bb7.  Here we're ahead a pawn but White does have a lead in development and definite compensation. That being said, as long as Black develops and contains white's play then Black will be better in the long run.   Next we will play ...a6 to prevent Bb5 ideas, ...Be7, ...O-O and move the queen back to c6 if it is attacked.} 
