3. Nc3 {Usually when White doesn't defend their d4-pawn with another pawn then I am recommending that we make the pawn trade and force White to recapture with a piece. However, here it is a bit different. We can play the simple move ...d5 (which is typically a common response to the Trompowsky) and it is especially good for us here since the knight on c3 is blocking white's own c-pawn from being useful.} 
3. d5 {This position can also be reached through the move order1.d4Nf62.Nc3d53.Bg5c5.} 
4. e3
4. cxd4
5. exd4
5. Nc6 {Another position where Black has an easy game. White's knight on c3 is a bit misplaced and the bishop on g5 isn't doing much either. We will play ...Bf5, ...e6, ...Be7 or ...Bd6 and castle the king. If our pawns do end up getting doubled on the f-file then we may prefer to castle queenside.} 
