3. c3 {White defends the d4-pawn but still has problems to solve.} 
3. Ne4 {Again avoiding the piece trade and harassing the bishop.} 
4. Bf4
4. Qb6
5. Qc2 {White may try to defend their b2-pawn while counterattacking our e4-knight but we don't need to react to this threat since ...Qxb2 trapping the rook would be our answer. Let's see how many moves in a row we can leave the knight "hanging"!} 
5. cxd4
6. cxd4 {Keep in mind that the c8-bishop is actually hanging this time!} 
6. Nc6
7. e3
7. Nb4 {Continuing to ignore the "attack" on our e4-knight!} 
8. Qxe4 {White might think they can capture the knight on e4 now since we cannot respond with ...Qxb2 but there is another problem for them...} 
8. d5 {Now the queen must give up the defense of the c2-square and we will fork there followed by winning the rook in the corner. Always try to ignore your opponent's "threats" if possible and play actively instead! Passive defense should be the last resort.} 
