1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky can be a good surprise weapon for players who want to avoid mainline opening theory and still get a game with interesting imbalances. Typically White is looking to trade the bishop for knight on f6 which results in the imbalance of Black having a compromised doubled-pawn structure but in return Black gains the bishop pair.} 
2. c5 {The move I'm recommending is 2...c5 which keeps our opening repertoire easy to remember. We're going to play 2...c5 against almost every move that White can throw at us.   There will be a few exceptions to this but that will tend to be the game plan. The idea behind 2...c5 is that we want to start a fight against White's d4-pawn as quickly as possible.   If we can chip away at it then we can look to gain a space advantage ourselves in the center as the game progresses. Also, we open up the d8-a5 diagonal for our queen which will tend to go towards the b6-square in a lot of situations. From b6 the queen will put more pressure on the d4-pawn as well as the undefended b2-pawn.} 
3. Bxf6 {White follows through with their most common plan of trading the bishop for the knight.} 
3. gxf6 {It is usually best to recapture towards the center of the board and that is what we do here. This f6-pawn will help us in our fight against white's center too.} 
4. dxc5 {Capturing on c5 wins a pawn in the short-term but we will regain it without much trouble and then be left with a central pawn advantage.} 
4. e6
5. Nd2
5. Bxc5
6. Ne4 {It might seem like White has gotten us into a tricky spot with Nxc5 and Nd6+ both being annoying threats. We have a good answer for this though!} 
6. Bb4+ {This might seem like a wasted move but there is an important follow-up coming.} 
7. c3
7. d5 {Now the point is revealed. We don't mind trading knight for bishop but we're going to do it in a way that also gives White doubled pawns themselves.} 
8. cxb4
8. dxe4
9. Qxd8+
9. Kxd8 {Black has a bit of an advantage here despite having an extra pair of doubled pawns. The reason we are better is that our doubled f- and e-pawns control a ton of central space and our pieces are easy to get into the game. Also, the centralized king is not an issue without queens on the board. Finally, if White plays e3 to develop their light-square bishop then we can maneuver our knight to e5 and try to take advantage of the weak d3-square.} 
