[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Jobava London"]
[Black "2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Bf4 {The 'Jobava London' has been popularized in recent years as an opening that is good for aggressive players. Compared to the tamer London System, White has put their knight on c3 rather than a pawn. This has advantages but also disadvantages.   The advantage to white's set-up is that the knight can be aggressively used with various Nb5 jumps and e4 pawn breaks. The downside is that the d5-pawn is a bit harder to break down with typical c4-pawn breaks since the knight is in the way of the pawn.   The way I recommend playing against the Jobava London System is nothing new but I do find it to fit in nicely with our repertoire since an early ...c5 pawn break is used.3.Bg5c5Transposes to the Trompowsky chapter HERE.} 
3. c5 {Similar to the Trompowsky 3. Nc3 variation, we use the same pawn break to attack white's central d4-pawn. We are taking advantage of the fact that White cannot solidify their central d4-pawn with c3 since the knight is in the way. This is different from the London System where White would be able to respond with c3 if they wanted to.} 
4. e4 {White's second-most popular move and one we should be ready for. They look to make a pawn break and open the center of the board using their slight lead in development.} 
4. cxd4 {I like the option of pulling white's queen to the d4-square and into the line of fire for our pieces.} 
5. Nb5 {We always need to be alert to these knight jumps, aiming towards the c7-square. Here it is not working for White though due to our energetic response.} 
5. e5 {Another e-pawn sacrifice in order to accelerate our development. We hit the bishop and prevent the immediate Nc7+ while also opening up our own bishop on f8.} 
6. Bxe5
6. Bb4+
7. c3
7. dxc3 {We threaten various discovered checks such as c2+ and cxb2+ which means that White must recapture on c3.} 
8. bxc3 {8.Nc7+??This doesn't work and loses a piece for White.8...Qxc79.Bxc7c2+We gave up our queen but regain the material due to this discovered check tactic.10.Qd2Bxd2+11.Kxd2Nxe4+-+White is in huge trouble. They cannot capture the c2-pawn due to the capture on f2. White will be left down two pawns in a lost position.} 
8. Ba5 {Now we cover the c7-square so that the fork isn't possible.} 
9. Nd6+ {White takes advantage of our bishop no longer defending the d6-square but this is not a big problem for us.} 
9. Kf8 {Now we want to play ...Nc6 and attack white's e5-bishop which is defending both the c3-pawn and d6-knight.} 
10. Ne2 {White adds additional defense to the c3-pawn.} 
10. Nc6
11. Bf4
11. Nxe4 {The simplest move. We want to trade pieces to avoid more danger with our king.} 
12. Qxd5
12. Nxd6
13. Bxd6+ {Overly amibitous. White's queen will be a target in the center of the board.} 
13. Kg8
14. O-O-O
14. Be6
15. Qd3
15. h5 {Our king is actually much safer than white's king at this point! We will play ...Rh6 to activate our kingside rook and work to attack white's weakened queenside.} 
