6. dxe4 {It may seem counter-intuitive to open the center when White has a lead in development but we will be able to punish white's multiple queen moves better this way.} 
7. Rd1 {White develops their rook with tempo but this also allows us to break the pin on our knight with development.} 
7. Bd7 {Now ...e5 is an idea.} 
8. Nxe4 {If White captures on e4 too quickly then we get a crushing advantage due to discovered attacks against white's queen soon.} 
8. e5 {Attacking the bishop but also giving our knight the ability to go to d4 with a discovered attack against white's queen.} 
9. Nxf6+
9. gxf6 {Keeping the e5-pawn secure despite giving ourselves doubled pawns. White has only one way to deal with an incoming ...Nd4 threat easily while also saving their f4-bishop.} 
10. Qe4
10. Qb6 {The b2-pawn is awkard to defend.} 
11. Bc1
11. Bc5 {We have a huge lead in development and a ton of pressure against white's f2-pawn. Next we'll castle queenside and play around the center of the board with moves like ...Nd4, ...f5 and ...Rg8 will be good too.} 
