[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Jobava London"]
[Black "2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 #7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Bf4 {The 'Jobava London' has been popularized in recent years as an opening that is good for aggressive players. Compared to the tamer London System, White has put their knight on c3 rather than a pawn. This has advantages but also disadvantages.   The advantage to white's set-up is that the knight can be aggressively used with various Nb5 jumps and e4 pawn breaks. The downside is that the d5-pawn is a bit harder to break down with typical c4-pawn breaks since the knight is in the way of the pawn.   The way I recommend playing against the Jobava London System is nothing new but I do find it to fit in nicely with our repertoire since an early ...c5 pawn break is used.3.Bg5c5Transposes to the Trompowsky chapter HERE.} 
3. c5 {Similar to the Trompowsky 3. Nc3 variation, we use the same pawn break to attack white's central d4-pawn. We are taking advantage of the fact that White cannot solidify their central d4-pawn with c3 since the knight is in the way. This is different from the London System where White would be able to respond with c3 if they wanted to.} 
4. e4 {White's second-most popular move and one we should be ready for. They look to make a pawn break and open the center of the board using their slight lead in development.} 
4. cxd4 {I like the option of pulling white's queen to the d4-square and into the line of fire for our pieces.} 
5. Qxd4
5. Nc6
6. Qa4 {White is moving their queen too many times. Interestingly enough, grandmaster Olexandr Bortnyk has played this way as White a lot of times with good results. Objectively this move is not as good as the mainline Bb5 though.} 
6. dxe4 {It may seem counter-intuitive to open the center when White has a lead in development but we will be able to punish white's multiple queen moves better this way.} 
7. Nxe4 {Capturing back on e4 is going to run into the same response as Nb5 would.} 
7. e5 {We gain space in the center, harass white's bishop and look to play ...Bb4+ soon.} 
8. Bxe5 {The pawn is poisoned!} 
8. Bb4+ {Aside from the check, we are also now cutting off white's queen from defending their e4-knight so that ... Nxe4 is a threat too.} 
9. Nc3 {Blocking with the knight keeps the knight safe but allows a pin along the e-file.} 
9. Qe7 {White is ahead a pawn but will have big trouble defending against our e-file pin. Black is completely winning here since we can play ...Bd7 or ...O-O after White defends the bishop.} 
