10. Qb6 {An absolutely necessary move. We cannot afford to allow white's queen to stay well-placed in the center of the board for long.} 
11. Qd2 {White should avoid the queen trade since getting queens off the board will make our life so much easier.} 
11. d4 {I recommend this straight-forward way of getting to an equal endgame. We give the pawn back for a moment but will get the g2-pawn in return. White must capture the d4-pawn with the knight or queen. If they play something like Ne2 instead then we can play ...Bxf3 followed by ...e5 with a big advantage.} 
12. Qxd4 {White decides to trade queens immediately.} 
12. Qxd4
13. Nxd4
13. Bxg2
14. Rg1 {14.Nxe6??Trying to counterattack and threaten Nc7+ fails for White.14...Bxh115.Nc7+Kd816.Nxa8e517.Be3b6-+White's knight is trapped and we threaten ...Bxa8.} 
14. e5 {It is important for us to continue to dictate the pace of the game with our own forcing moves since playing a defensive move like ...Bh3 would allow White to turn the pressure on us.} 
15. Bxe5 {15.Rxg2?!This is an inaccurate capture for White.15...exd416.Nb5Rc8∓We threaten ...Rxc2 as well as ...e5 or ...a6. White is in some trouble here, especially if ...e5 can be played.} 
15. Nxe5
16. Rxg2
16. O-O-O {We've entered equality territory and many moves are possible from here.} 
17. Ne6 {This fork may look dangerous but it is not an issue at all.} 
17. Rd6
18. Nxf8
18. Rxf8
19. Rxg7
19. Nf3+
20. Kf1
20. Rd2 {White cannot defend the c2-pawn without running into trouble with the f2-pawn.} 
21. Ne4
21. Rxc2
22. Rxe7
22. Rg8 {We threaten mate on g1 which forces White to play Ng3. After this move we can then capture the h2-pawn and later the b2-pawn as well. The resulting endgame is completely equal and should result in a draw.} 
