5. exd4
5. Bg4 {I like this move. It scores very well in the database (about a 63% score for Black) and makes it difficult for White to play the way they usually want to play. We try to provoke the pawn to f3 which makes white's kingside play in the Carlsbad formation more difficult to accomplish.} 
6. Be2 {White blocks the threat with their bishop but we are happy to trade light-square bishops since our g4-bishop is our bad bishop.} 
6. Bxe2
7. Ngxe2 {The knight is not ideally placed on e2. It should be on f3 and go to e5 later.} 
7. Nc6
8. O-O
8. e6 {We get into a perfectly fine middlegame soon with ...Be7 and ...O-O coming next. Because we've already traded one pair of bishops then we don't need to play ... Bd6 as much since there is only one bishop remaining on the board for each player. Our plan for the middlegame is to expand on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5 and play down the half-open c-file.} 
