4. cxd4 {The mainline response. Both solid and good. We trade pawns on d4 and will eventually get into a Carlsbad formation but with White lacking the ability to play c3 easily. We'll discuss this a bit more further down the variations.} 
5. exd4
5. Bg4 {I like this move. It scores very well in the database (about a 63% score for Black) and makes it difficult for White to play the way they usually want to play. We try to provoke the pawn to f3 which makes white's kingside play in the Carlsbad formation more difficult to accomplish.} 
6. Nf3 {White develops their knight but pins it themselves.} 
6. Nc6
7. Be2
7. e6
8. O-O
8. Bd6 {We should trade off one pair of bishops to begin with. Playing ...Be7 is also okay too but I prefer to eliminate the f4-bishop since we may need to put a rook on b8 later to help with our queenside play.} 
9. Ne5 {White hops into e5 but allows a light-square bishop trade.} 
9. Bxe2
10. Nxe2
10. Qc7
11. Nxc6
11. bxc6 {It may seem a bit odd to give ourselves a backward c-pawn but opening the b-file is useful and we will play ...c5 to trade off this pawn soon anyways.} 
12. Bxd6
12. Qxd6
13. Ng3
13. O-O
14. c3
14. c5 {We will trade off our c-pawn and leave White with no central pawn or an isolated d-pawn. Both cases are good for us and we can play around the files on the queenside while also having a central pawn majority.} 
