2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Bf4 {The 'Jobava London' has been popularized in recent years as an opening that is good for aggressive players. Compared to the tamer London System, White has put their knight on c3 rather than a pawn. This has advantages but also disadvantages.   The advantage to white's set-up is that the knight can be aggressively used with various Nb5 jumps and e4 pawn breaks. The downside is that the d5-pawn is a bit harder to break down with typical c4-pawn breaks since the knight is in the way of the pawn.   The way I recommend playing against the Jobava London System is nothing new but I do find it to fit in nicely with our repertoire since an early ...c5 pawn break is used.3.Bg5c5Transposes to the Trompowsky chapter HERE.} 
3. c5 {Similar to the Trompowsky 3. Nc3 variation, we use the same pawn break to attack white's central d4-pawn. We are taking advantage of the fact that White cannot solidify their central d4-pawn with c3 since the knight is in the way. This is different from the London System where White would be able to respond with c3 if they wanted to.} 
4. e3 {The most common move by a big margin. White reinforces their d4-pawn and opens up their light-square bishop.} 
4. cxd4 {The mainline response. Both solid and good. We trade pawns on d4 and will eventually get into a Carlsbad formation but with White lacking the ability to play c3 easily. We'll discuss this a bit more further down the variations.} 
5. exd4
5. Bg4 {I like this move. It scores very well in the database (about a 63% score for Black) and makes it difficult for White to play the way they usually want to play. We try to provoke the pawn to f3 which makes white's kingside play in the Carlsbad formation more difficult to accomplish.} 
6. f3 {The most common response. The downside to this move is that the f3-square is blocked so that white's knight cannot develop there anymore.} 
6. Bd7 {It's very important to go back to d7 so that we can deal with Nb5 jumps.} 
7. Nb5 {White threatens to fork on c7. We should eliminate this option by trading on b5 rather than playing ...Na6.} 
7. Bxb5
8. Bxb5+
8. Nc6
9. c3
9. e6 {We have reached a Carlsbad formation (f7-e6-d5 pawns vs b2-c3-d4 pawns). The general plan for each player is that White will play in the kingside direction and work to attack our king while Black will play in the queenside direction with a minority attack against white's pawn chain.   One big drawback to white's plan is that the pawn is on f3 though! This makes it more difficult for White to do things such as Nf3-e5 which would help their attack.   If the pawn was back on f2 instead, then the evaluation of the position jumps by about 0.5 for White. This is why we played ...Bg4 earlier to provoke the pawn to f3!   The game plan for Black is now to play ...Bd6 to trade off one of white's bishops in their pair, castle kingside and play around the queenside with ...a6, ...b5, ...Rfc8, ...Rab8 and work towards the b4-pawn break in order to create a weak pawn in white's queenside.} 
