10. g6 {White's pawns are all on the dark-squares which means the light-squares are weak (such as f5). While it is true that our pawns are on light-squares which gives us dark-square weaknesses ourselves, White will have a hard time taking advantage of this.} 
11. Nf3
11. Qb6 {Now that the kingside pawns are immobilized, it is time to play on the queenside.} 
12. Qd2 {White leaves the b2-pawn undefended and hopes that they'll be able to use the half-open b-file.} 
12. Qxb2
13. Rb1
13. Qa3 {White cannot capture the b7-pawn due to ...Bb4.} 
14. Be2
14. a6 {We prevent any Nb5 jumps and are up a clean extra pawn. White doesn't have enough compensation since their kingside attack is hard to continue due to the pawns being blockaded. We may maneuver our knight with ...Ng7-f5 soon and then develop the dark-square bishop afterwards.} 
