3. Bd3 {White goes for a Bd3/Nf3 set-up with or without f4 included. This move order is a bit more rare since the bishop doesn't contribute to the control of the center as much as the f-pawn or f3-knight.} 
3. d5
4. b3 {As we see in the 2. Nf3 c5 Sidelines chapter, when White plays b3 in these pawn structures we have a good answer.} 
4. cxd4 {We immediately trade pawns on d4 and point out that a bishop on b2 will be misplaced. If the bishop isn't going to b2 in the future then what was the purpose of playing b3?} 
5. exd4
5. Nc6
6. Bb2
6. Bg4
7. Nf3
7. Qa5+ {Playing ... e6 was fine but here we can cause trouble for White due to the bishop already being on the d3-square.} 
8. Nbd2 {8.c3?This loses a pawn for White.8...Bxf39.Qxf3Nxd4∓Taking advantage of the pin along the e1-a5 diagonal.8.Bc3The bishop is misplaced here.8...Qc7∓We simply retreat the queen and point out that the bishop on the c3-square makes no sense. Black has a comfortable game with ...e6, ...Bd6 and castling coming next.} 
8. Nb4 {Going for the good bishop on d3.} 
9. Be2
9. Bxf3 {An unexpected trade of pieces but we win material soon because of this.} 
10. Bxf3
10. Qc7 {The c2-pawn cannot be defended. If Rc1 then ...Nxa2 followed by returning the knight to b4 afterwards is great for us. If the c-pawn advances then we have ...Nd3+ forking the king and b2-bishop. This shows the point of trading on f3 earlier: We did it to pull the bishop away from the e2-square where it would have defended the d3-square.} 
