1. d4
1. Nf6 {Welcome to the second move sidelines chapter. Here we will be examining all of the moves that are not 2. c4, Nf3, Bf4, Bg5 or Nc3.   Each of those moves will have their own respective chapters. As is usual with many sidelines, the variations in this chapter will generally not put us under much pressure and we will have plenty of freedom to turn the pressure around on our own opponent.   Against pretty much every second move sideline option we will be responding with our typical 2...c5 strike against white's center and then White will have some options from there. Let's get to it!} 
2. e3 {White's most popular of the 'second move sidelines' but this will most likely transpose into a variation from a different chapter.} 
2. c5
3. d5 {Objectively white's best move but incredibly rare with this move order. No one plays 2. e3 to play 3. d5 aftewards. If someone is playing 2. e3 then they are playing much more reserved and less ambitious than this.} 
3. e6 {We look to immediately chip away at white's d5-pawn.} 
4. c4 {Defending d5 with another pawn.} 
4. exd5 {We can go for a good version of a Benoni pawn formation due to white's misplaced e-pawn.} 
5. cxd5
5. g6 {The next few moves will be ...Bg7, ... O-O, ...d6 and ...Re8 in some order. We don’t need to worry about White playing d6 quickly themselves since this pawn will usually turn out to be a liability rather than a strength.} 
6. Nc3
6. Bg7
7. Nf3
7. O-O
8. Be2
8. d6
9. O-O
9. Re8 {Usually in this pawn formation, White will have their e-pawn on e4 instead of e3 which would give them more control of the center and also open up their dark-square bishop at the same time.   Here playing e4 is not possible for White and we can play mostly around the queenside with moves like ...Na6-c7, ...a6 and ...b5.   Playing ...Ne4 will also be useful to eliminate the c3-knight so that the dark-square diagonal is opened up more for our g7-bishop.} 
