10. O-O {Up through here the entire mainline of the London System chapter has been followed by both sides with a slight move order change where White played h3 before Nf3.   CLICK HERE FOR A MORE IN-DEPTH EXPLANATION ABOUT THE MOVES LEADING UP TO THIS POSITION.   My conclusion in the theoretical chapter here was that ' The position is balanced with both sides having advantages and disadvantages. One plan to for go for soon is ...b5 and if White captures en passant then we can use the half-open b-file to attack on the queenside towards the b2-pawn'.   Let's see how Makarian executes this plan in the game.} 
11. O-O
11. b5 {11...cxd4It may be a tiny bit more precise to capture on d4 in this situation before White gets the chance to play d5. We will still follow-up with ...b5 afterwards anyways but if White plays d5 later then they will not be able to support it with an e-pawn.12.exd4b513.axb6Nxb6We get the same play on the queenside without White having the ability to play d5. If they play d5 now then the pawn will immediately become a weakness after ...Bb7. Also, because the e-pawn is gone, our light-square bishop can develop a bit easier since ...Bf5 will not get hit by e4 and ...Bb7 will not be blocked in by d5.} 
12. axb6
12. Nxb6
13. d5 {White has been able to achieve d5 and will aim to reinforce the pawn with e4 soon. If this is achieved then it is not necessarily a problem for us at all but I like what Black did here to make this e4 advance more difficult.} 
13. Nh5
14. Bh2
14. f5 {A key move to the sequence. Black prevents White from advancing e4 easily. This move does weaken the e6-square but Black has ways to deal with that. By preventing e4, Black is semi-isolating white's d5-pawn which now has some trouble being defended by a friendly pawn.} 
15. Nd2
15. Bxc3 {Black decides to cash in and win the d5-pawn while weakening white's queenside pawn structure. This does come at the cost of the bishop pair though which means that White will have some compensation for the pawn deficit.15...Nf6This was the more solid option, keeping the bishop pair alive and looking to target the d5-pawn in the long-run. The downside to this is that White doesn't have to lose the d5-pawn immediately as they did in the game.16.Bf3a5⩱Next we play ... a4, ...Ba6 and ...Rfb8. White's pieces are much less active than ours and they have no targets to attack either while we have the d5-pawn and b2-pawn to hit.} 
16. bxc3
16. Nxd5
17. Bc4 {Rather than go for the capture on h5, White decides to make a pin.17.Bxh5?!This capture looks good for White due to weakening our kingside and seemingly winning a pawn back but everything ends up good for Black.17...Nxc3!A nice in-between move that requires some calculation to pull off.18.Qf3gxh5!Leaving the rook on a1 open to capture. However, capturing it would lose the queen.19.Qxh5(19.Qxa8??Bb720.Qa7Ne2+Setting up a discovered attack).(20...Nb5-+This traps the queen as well.21.Kh1Bxg2+!22.Kxg2Qxa7-+)19...Bb7⩱White has messed up our kingside a bit but they are still down a pawn and Black is better off.} 
17. Be6 {17...e6?Defending the knight with the e-pawn would be a fatal mistake.18.Bxd5exd519.Nc4!White opens up the queen's attack on the d5-square while also attacking the d6-pawn at the same time.19...dxc420.Qd5++-Forking the king and rook.} 
18. e4
18. fxe4
19. Nxe4
19. Ndf4
20. Bxe6+
20. Nxe6
21. Qd5 {White continues to keep the pressure up on Black. From their point of view they are playing in the right way. They are down a pawn with a worse pawn structure   (doubled, isolated c-pawns) so they need to create dynamic counterplay or else they will lose in the long-run.} 
21. Nhg7 {And in response, Black needs to hold the position together, weather the short-term storm that White creates and try to maintain their static/long-term advantage.} 
22. Ng5
22. Qc8 {Now ...Rf5 is a threat.} 
23. g4 {Preventing ...Rf5 but weakening their kingside.} 
23. h6 {Kicking white's pieces backwards. Black is starting to regain control of the game.} 
24. Nf3
24. Kh7 {Stepping out of the pin.} 
25. Nh4
25. Nf4
26. Bxf4 {Trading pieces does eliminate the strong f4-knight but also works towards black's long-term gameplan of trading material, consolidating their advantage and then pressing forward in the endgame.} 
26. Rxf4
27. Rfe1
27. Ra7
28. Qd3
28. Rf6 {Keeping the g6-pawn defended.} 
29. Re4 {With ideas of doubling rooks on the e-file or a-file.} 
29. e5 {Black makes progress in the kingside half of the board and keeps the e-pawn secure but ends up losing the a-pawn soon.29...a5!Keeping the a-pawn alive was probably a bit better compared to losing it.30.Rea4Qa8-+} 
30. Rea4 {White hunts down black's a-pawn and will equalize material but still be left over with the worse long-term position due to their weakened kingside and bad c-pawns.} 
30. Qe6
31. Rxa6
31. e4
32. Qg3
32. Rd7 {32...Raf7∓This was a bit more of an active way to play. The d-pawn is already defended twice on the sixth-rank so the rook wasn't necessary on the d7-square. Instead, it should be on the f-file helping to attack the f2-pawn.} 
33. Ra7
33. g5
34. Nf5 {White cracks under the pressure and ends up blundering (sacrificing?) a pawn.34.Ng2This was absolutely necessary. White probably didn't like the look of the following sequence though.34...Rf335.Qh2White's queen is stuck on h2 but at least White isn't down a pawn (yet).35...Rxc3?!Capturing the c-pawn ends up letting white's knight into the game.36.Ne3±Despite being down a pawn, white's knight is much more useful than black's knight and black's rook on c3 is stranded. There is definite compensation for White here.} 
34. Nxf5
35. gxf5
35. Qxf5 {Black is up a pawn and White has no compensation for it.} 
36. Qg4 {White decides to risk the game on a miscalculation by Black but they were up to the task and finish the game efficiently.} 
36. Qxf2+
37. Kh1
37. Rxa7
