11. Nbd2 {Up through here the entire line of the 2. Nf3 London System chapter has been followed by both sides with a slight move order change where I played Nc6 before Qb6.   CLICK HERE FOR A MORE IN-DEPTH EXPLANATION ABOUT THE MOVES LEADING UP TO THIS POSITION.} 
11. h5 {In the course I have recommended 11...Bg7 here but in this game I played 11...h5 with potential ideas of putting the bishop on h6 in some situations. However, in the game it never ended up happening and I do put the bishop on g7 very soon. Part of the reason for the difference with this move compared to what I recommend in the repertoire is that I was very early on in working on this repertoire for myself when I played this game and was trying a few different set-ups in various games. Let's see how I was able to make good use of the bishop pair and create a strong attack in this game.11...Bg7In the repertoire I recommend the move 11...Bg7 and conclude that 'Black has a nice position with the bishop pair and better pawn structure'.} 
12. b3 {White chips away at the c4-pawn but ends up weakening their c3-pawn in the long-term.} 
12. cxb3
13. axb3
13. Rc8 {Lining up for potential ...Nb4 moves using the pin on the c-file.} 
14. Qb2
14. Bg7 {I want to play ...e5 soon here in order to open up the center of the board and improve my bishops.} 
15. Nh4 {White begins a faulty plan trying to prevent my ...e5 advance.} 
15. Bg4
16. f4 {It seems like ...e5 has been prevented. However, a good question to ask yourself when you have a good positional move that looks like it's not working is 'what if I do it anyways?'} 
16. e5 {We can make the ...e5 advance work tactically since white's e3-pawn is undefended behind their d4-pawn.} 
17. Nhf3 {White brings the knight back to the center but the damage has already been done.17.fxe5Bxe5!Threatening mate on g3.18.Kf2(18.dxe5??Qxe3+Black is checkmated next move).18...Bb8-+White's king is extremely weak and exposed and Black is much better.} 
17. O-O {I decide to delay the decision on capturing the f4 or d4-pawns since my e5-pawn can still not be captured safely without repercussion. Also, because my pawn is still on e5, it is not possible for White to develop their bishop to d3 due to the ...e4 pawn fork.17...exd418.exd4O-O19.Bd3Rfe8+20.Kf2-+This position is still very good for Black but at least White got the bishop to d3 which is more active than being on e2.} 
18. Be2 {18.fxe5Probably White needed to capture on e5 anyways and keep the e3-pawn alive in order to keep the e-file semi-closed.18...Nxe519.Be2(19.dxe5??Qxe3+20.Be2Bxe5-+White will not survive the incoming attack).19...Nd7-+White's position is still miserable, but maybe they can hold things together somewhat with Kf2.} 
18. exd4 {Now I capture on d4 to open up the e- or c-file.} 
19. exd4
19. Rfe8
20. Kf1
20. Re3 {Improving all the pieces to the maximum. I want to target the c3-pawn, bishop and maybe even the g3-pawn horizonatally too.} 
21. Rc1
21. Ne7 {Maneuvering the knight to f5 where it will continue to hit the d4-pawn but also attack the g3-pawn.} 
22. Nb1
22. Nf5
23. Kf2
23. Rce8 {Every piece is particpitaing to the maximum here and tactics are bound to occur soon.} 
24. Bd1 {Our pieces cannot be improved any further. Also, white's pieces look horrible. Now is the time to calculate and make something happen.} 
24. Bxf3
25. gxf3
25. Nxd4 {Winning a pawn but more importantly, opening up the a1-h8 and a7-g1 diagonals for my bishop and queen. White's king will not survive for long and they ended up resigning here.} 
