*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {This chapter will include 50 puzzles from various games that began with the repertoire seen throughout this course or from very similar opening variations.   You will be given a position and then get the chance to find the best move or sequence of moves in the position which will get you the biggest advantage possible. I have taken a small liberty with some of the examples where the specific move sequence played in the game gives you many different strong moves available whereas the puzzles here in this chapter will only have one best answer in each position (unless noted in the annotations). There will not be an order to the puzzles in terms of difficulty.   You may have an easy puzzle followed by a more difficult puzzle then another easy puzzle after that. Try to treat each puzzle as if you were playing that position in a game of your own and take your time to think through things. Happy solving!} 1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Ibanez Lozano, Antonio vs. Cifuentes Parada, Roberto"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p2nppbp/1p3np1/3p4/3NP3/2PB4/PP1N1PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 10"]
[Result "*"]

10. Nc5 {Attacking both the bishop and e4-pawn.} 
11. Bc2
11. dxe4
12. Nxe4 {White captures the pawn back automatically but ends up losing a piece.} 
12. Nfxe4
13. Bxe4
13. Nxe4
14. Rxe4
14. e5 {White loses the knight due to the pin along the d-file.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Nadir, Samir vs. Magerramov, Elmar S"]
[FEN "rbbqr1k1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/1N1p4/8/PPN1P3/4BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[Result "*"]

12. a6 {Black kicks the knight away from controlling the c7-square.} 
13. Nd4
13. Nxd4
14. exd4 {White should capture with the queen but would still be at a big disadvantage after the move ...Be5.} 
14. Qc7 {White loses a piece due to the fork on h2 and c3.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Fernandez Vazquez, Jorge vs. Rodriguez Redondo, Ethan"]
[FEN "1nb2rk1/3p1ppp/1q1r1b2/2p5/2B1P3/8/PPQ1NPPP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 14"]
[Result "*"]

14. Qb4+ {Forking the king and c4-bishop. White doesn't have a good way to deal with the check.} 
15. Kf1 {15.Bd2Blocking with the bishop avoids an immediate loss but Black will have a very large advantage.15...Rxd216.Qxd2Qxc4-+Black is ahead two pieces against a rook with a big advantage.} 
15. Qxc4 {White loses massive material due to the need to protect the d1-square to avoid back-rank checkmate.} 
